<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attempted Chinese Hijacking Foiled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A man who attempted to hijack a Chinese domestic
airliner was killed by on-board security using the hijacker's own
knife, an airline spokesman and state media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's pilot and co-pilot were injured in the botched
hijacking Wednesday morning, but no passengers were hurt and the
plane landed safely, the Beijing Youth Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
   The man entered the cockpit brandishing a knife and what
appeared to be a handgun about five minutes after the Beijing-bound
Xinhua Airlines flight took off from Baotou, in China's Inner
Mongolian region, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   An airline spokesman who declined to give his name confirmed the
newspaper's account:
</P>
<P>
   The man demanded the plane, a Boeing 737, fly south, but grew
agitated as fuel on board began to run low. He stabbed the pilot
and co-pilot with his knife. Desperate security officers and crew
members, aided by two passengers, then assaulted the hijacker,
breaking his gun, which they then discovered to be fake.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing struggle, the man was beaten with a police club
and stabbed with his own weapon, dying on the spot, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane then landed at the closest airport, in the city of
Jinan, about 190 miles south of Beijing, just over two hours after
taking off. All 143 passengers were safe, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper ran a photo of what it said was the dead hijacker, his
hands and face covered in blood.
</P>
<P>
   China Central Television's Web site gave the surname of the
hijacker as Li, and said he was a 33-year-old unemployed man from
Baotou.
</P>
<P>
   The reports and airline spokesman gave no further details and
did not specify the hijacker's intended destination.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese hijackers have in the past mostly demanded to be flown
to Taiwan, Beijing's rival in an unfinished civil war, which lies
about 1,000 miles southeast of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   China strengthened airport security following a series of
hijackings to Taiwan in the early 1990s. But hijackings still
occur. On Jan. 29 this year, a man with a knife and a gasoline bomb
tried to commandeer a domestic flight bound for the southern city
of Fuzhou to Taiwan but the crew stopped him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
