<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-academy employee gets 41 months for arranging tryst with 'boy'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - It appears that a longtime employee of a
prestigious Pennsylvania military academy had sexual encounters
with at least two boys, one of them a cadet, a federal prosecutor
told a judge at the man's sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Hopkinson Jr. was sentenced Wednesday to the maximum 41
months in federal prison for crossing state lines to have sex with
someone he believed to be a New Jersey teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ''Billy'' was actually an undercover FBI agent who met Hopkinson
in an Internet chat room where adults have been known to seek
juveniles for sex, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The computer specialist has not been charged with any actual
sexual encounters, but a prosecutor told U.S. District Judge
Garrett E. Brown Jr. that Hopkinson had told a former colleague at
Valley Forge Military Academy and College he did have sex with a
cadet.
</P>
<P>
   The school maintains he had no improper contact with any of the
800 students at the all-male school, who range in age from 12 to
21. No students, faculty or staff have been associated with his
criminal activity, school spokeswoman Heather Swech said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson, 50, worked at Valley Forge for 25 years before
resigning days before his arrest April 21, 1999, at a central New
Jersey mall where he thought he would meet ''Billy.'' Hopkinson had
lived on the campus of the school in Wayne, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Brown ordered Hopkinson to undergo sex offender treatment while
serving his term, which must be served without parole, and to pay a
$10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   He barred Hopkinson from working with children or having access
to computer networks for three years after his release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Among the letters the judge received was a ''character
reference'' from Rep. Joseph M. Hoeffel III, D-Pa., who represents
most of Montgomery County in suburban Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel said he and Hopkinson attended high school together, but
have rarely seen each other since, ''mostly at reunions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While we weren't close friends, I admired his quiet
determination and good citizenship. I have only favorable and fond
memories of Jim's role in our class and school,'' Hoeffel said in
the handwritten note on his personal stationery.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel said Wednesday that he does not condone Hopkinson's
crimes. The first-term congressman noted that he did not ask the
judge for leniency in the letter, which he said was written as a
friend of the family after being contacted by Hopkinson's father.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Donna A. Krappa told the judge that the
FBI uncovered evidence that exploiting teens was ''a way of life
for Jim Hopkinson.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, however, was unable to locate the cadet Hopkinson
supposedly had sex with, Krappa said.
</P>
<P>
   The information came from a person who is now a vice principal
at a Philadelphia area high school. The educator, who Krappa would
not name, told the FBI that Hopkinson told him he had the cadet in
his apartment, showed him a ''hard core homosexual movie'' and then
engaged in a sexual act.
</P>
<P>
   The educator provided some identifying information, but did not
have the cadet's name, Krappa said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI searched Hopkinson's computer and found evidence he had
been in contact with boys, including one who was traumatized after
a sexual encounter with Hopkinson, Krappa told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The teen, who she referred to as ''M.R.,'' lived in the
Philadelphia area and was interviewed by the FBI, she said. He had
flashbacks for six months and remains under psychiatric treatment
more than a year after the incident, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson had been under house arrest after his arrest but has
been jailed since Jan. 14 upon release from hospital following a
suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson pleaded guilty in July to a charge of traveling
interstate to engage in a sexual act with a minor. He also pleaded
guilty to a charge filed in Pennsylvania of possession of child
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Krappa said authorities searched Hopkinson's home on the day he
traveled to New Jersey and found magazines that contained child
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   The collection included 20 years of publications from the North
American Man-Boy Love Association, which advocates sex between men
and boys, Krappa said.
</P>
<P>
   A message seeking comment Wednesday from Hopkinson lawyer
Michael Holsten was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Forge, founded in 1928, is the alma mater of Gen. H.
Norman Schwarzkopf and author J.D. Salinger. Its 120-acre campus is
15 miles west of Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
