<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
Frank Albert Disney
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Dr. Frank Albert Disney, a pediatrician
credited with popularizing office-based clinical research, died
Sept. 18 after a lengthy illness. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Disney and Dr. Burtis Breese started the longtime
practice in pediatrics of combining clinical practice with
office-based studies of strep throat and related childhood
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of World War II, Disney directed the Rochester
Blood Bank, then one of less than a half-dozen blood collection
centers in the nation.
</P>
<P>
Art Edgerton
</P>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- Art Edgerton, a broadcast reporter who took
his notes in Braille, died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Edgerton, who was born blind, also was a musician and community
activist. He learned to play the drums at age 9 and later played
the piano with bands and won a talent contest at the Apollo Theater
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Edgerton was director of public and community affairs for Clear
Channel Communications Inc. in Toledo. He also hosted and played
keyboards for weekend shows on WCWA-AM in Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   He began his broadcast career in 1957 at the former WTOL Radio
as a part-time disc jockey. He later became a radio and television
reporter.
</P>
<P>
Bob Hurt
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Bob Hurt, the driver who became a paraplegic
when he broke his neck trying to qualify for the 1968 Indianapolis
500, died in his sleep Sept. 23. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt died at a hotel in Toronto where he was undergoing
treatment for prostate cancer, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He began his auto-racing career at 19, driving modified stock
cars and sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt drove his own Ferrari to victory in the Puerto Rico Grand
Prix in 1962 and competed in a Lotus 18 as well as driving USAC
stock cars in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt never drove in the Indy 500. In 1964, he passed his rookie
test but did not make an attempt to qualify. In 1967, he qualified
at 161.261 mph, but he was bumped from the field by a faster
qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, rain marred practice and qualifying for 23 consecutive
days, so an extra qualifying day was added May 27 to fill the
field. Hurt was injured in the morning practice period.
</P>
<P>
Aleksandras Lileikis
</P>
<P>
   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) -- Aleksandras Lileikis, indicted for
sending scores of Jews to their deaths while he headed this city's
security police during World War II, died Tuesday of a heart
attack. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Nazi hunters sought for years to bring Lileikis, considered one
of the last major Nazi war criminals, to justice. He was indicted
by Lithuanian prosecutors, but the trial that began in 1998 never
went beyond the preliminary stages.
</P>
<P>
   Lileikis maintained his innocence throughout the on-again,
off-again court proceedings and claimed in a recent memoir that he
actively backed the anti-Nazi resistance and tried to foil the
massacres of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Lileikis was charged with genocide for allegedly turning Jews
over to be executed during the 1941-44 German occupation, when he
headed the Vilnius security police. His alleged victims were shot
in sand pits near Vilnius.
</P>
<P>
   Lileikis emigrated to the United States after the war and lived
in Norwood, Mass., where he worked in publishing. He returned to
Lithuania in 1996 as a U.S. court moved to revoke his citizenship
for lying about his Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
Frank Wills
</P>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Frank Wills, the Watergate security guard
who discovered the 1972 break-in that led to President Nixon's
resignation, died Wednesday. He was 52.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the family told The Augusta (Ga.) Chronicle that he
suffered a brain tumor and had been ill for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had spent the years since the break-in in relative
obscurity, Wills' discovery on the midnight shift at the
Washington, D.C., hotel-office complex thrust him briefly into the
spotlight. He later played himself in the movie ''All the
President's Men,'' about the scandal that brought down Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Early on June 17, 1972, Wills found a piece of tape over a door
latch leading into the Watergate complex. Thinking a shift worker
had put it there to make getting in and out of the building easier,
he simply pulled it off and stuffed it into his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   When he later found a second piece of tape over the lock, he
called the police.
</P>
<P>
   Wills followed the officers to the Democratic National Committee
offices in the Watergate. Inside, they found five men: James
McCord, Bernard Barker, Eugenio Martinez, Frank Sturgis and
Virgilio Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   The bungled burglary led to discoveries of conspiracy,
obstruction of justice, illegal use of the FBI and CIA and illegal
campaign contributions, all of which ultimately drove Nixon from
the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
