<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Menninger Clinic Moving to Texas  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID MILES
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) -- The Menninger Clinic, a world renowned
campus for the mentally ill that has struggled financially, is
moving to Texas despite a multimillion-dollar package designed to
keep it in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walter Menninger, the chief executive officer, told hundreds
of employees Wednesday that the clinic will become a partner with
the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston and the Methodist Health
Care System.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday night, he said the three
organizations will establish a national psychiatric center and a
brain and behavior research institute. A final agreement should be
reached by February.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Menninger and Baylor had committed to raise at
least $200 million in endowment funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that this alliance will allow Menninger to continue
growing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger said the clinic would be out of business in six to
eight years unless it moves from Topeka, where it was founded in
1925.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't intend for Menninger to be one of the casualties in
the shakeout of health care,'' he said. ''I'm certain that many
people feel frustrated about this, but it is our reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Menninger officials acknowledged earlier this year that changes
in psychiatric care and the reimbursement policies of health
insurance companies had forced them to consider relocating to a
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic has had financial problems for at least a decade and
last year lost $2.9 million despite using $12 million of its
endowment to defray operating expenses. The clinic also is facing
an increased use of drugs instead of therapy to treat mental
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger said the clinic planned to relocate its education,
research and national services programs to Houston by 2002. He said
the 1,162 full- and part-time staffers in Topeka will be offered
incentives to stay with the clinic, but some jobs will be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The Menninger trustees rejected proposals from the University of
Kansas Medical Center in Kansas City and the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Gov. Bill Graves announced an incentive
package worth nearly $100 million designed to keep the clinic in
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic was founded by Karl Menninger; his father, Charles;
and a brother, William. Karl Menninger became a giant in
psychiatry, writing influential books such as ''The Human Mind''
and ''Love Against Hate,'' and he is credited with convincing the
American public that mental disorders could be treated and cured.
</P>
<P>
   The founders converted a farmhouse into a clinic with 13 beds.
It still stands in Topeka but has been converted into a bed and
breakfast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 0008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
