<DOCNO> APW20000928.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Reaches Compromise Over Iraq  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council reached a compromise
agreement Wednesday on yet another challenge to sanctions against
Iraq that had threatened a $15.9 billion payout to Kuwait's oil
company.
</P>
<P>
   France, Russia and China agreed to let the payment go through at
Thursday's meeting of the U.N. Compensation Commission in Geneva as
long as the United States and Britain support a reduction in the
amount of money that the fund receives from the U.N. oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
   The three countries, Iraq's strongest supporters on the Security
Council, had sought to delay payment to the Kuwait Petroleum Co.,
saying such a large award to a corporation was unconscionable at a
time when Iraqis are suffering from decade-old sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 30 percent of every dollar Iraq earns through the
program is diverted to the fund to compensate victims of Iraq's
1990 invasion of Kuwait. The bulk of the remainder is used to buy
humanitarian goods for Iraqis who are suffering under sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise deal, which the full 15-member council agreed to,
calls for the percentage to be reduced to 25 percent for the
six-month period that begins Dec. 6. The excess money, which would
amount to about $1 billion over a year under current oil prices,
would be targeted for humanitarian projects.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes against the backdrop of increasingly bold
attempts by Iraq's friends on the council -- France in particular --
to push the envelope on sanctions in Baghdad's favor, much to the
consternation of an increasingly isolated United States.
</P>
<P>
   France last week flouted procedures of the U.N. committee
monitoring sanctions against Iraq by sending a flight to Iraq
without giving committee members time to approve it -- a move the
United States said was a ''blatant violation'' of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent a flight over the weekend, without answering
questions raised by the United States and Britain, saying it only
had to notify the committee. A Jordanian flight flew to Baghdad on
Wednesday with full committee approval, after providing the United
States with information it wanted about the cargo.
</P>
<P>
   The flights have been a gray area for the council, with France
and Russia saying the committee need only be notified of proposed
flights. The United States and Britain say the committee must
actually approve them.
</P>
<P>
   But the compensation committee, made up of the 15 members of the
council, managed to remain relatively free of division, taking all
of its decisions by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian and French position on the Kuwait Petroleum Co.
claim had threatened to force a vote in the commission, which might
have politicized future compensation claims, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   At an OPEC summit in Caracas, Venezuela, Iraqi Deputy Foreign
Minister Riyadh Al-Qaisi derided the decision to allow the Kuwaiti
claim to go through, saying the United Nations should release Iraqi
funding so it can purchase food and humanitarian aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 0010 </TRAILER>
