<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Closing Fireworks To Be Big  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- It's being billed as the biggest
fireworks display in Australia, and certainly the most unique.
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic closing ceremony finishes Sunday night, an
8.5-mile set of timed fireworks called the ''River of Lightning''
will go off from the Olympic stadium to the Sydney Harbor Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive display -- 40 percent larger than Sydney's
millennium display -- will begin with the timed sequence of 24
firing positions along the 8.5 miles from Homebush Bay to the
bridge. More fireworks from the Harbor Bridge and four other launch
positions along the harbor will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic ceremonies artistic director David Atkins said the
''fuse'' from Homebush will take more than two minutes to trigger
the fireworks on the bridge. The shells, to be set off every six
seconds and last for 30 seconds, will be fired every 500 yards
along the river.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 2 million spectators are expected to cram the harbor
shores to watch the display, while 16 giant screens will broadcast
the event to city and regional centers in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's Seven television network will utilize the Goodyear
blimp and two helicopters as well as cameras from NBC, BBC, CBC
Canada, ZDF Germany and TV2 Denmark to broadcast the event.
</P>
<P>
   Pyrotechnists from five continents, representing the Olympic
rings, are each creating a three-minute display to be fired from
four harbor locations.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are Haga Fireworks Company in Miyagi, Japan; Pyro
Spectacular in Johannesburg, South Africa; Pirotecnia Ricarda
Caballer in Valencia, Spain; Alonzo Fireworks Display Inc. of New
York; and Foti International Fireworks from Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
