<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crew Stuck on Casino Boat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) -- Nearly 200 crew members on the
Texas Treasure casino ship are being sequestered as authorities
sort out their status, along with the boat's.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-passenger ship still makes its gambling cruises, but
the crew has to stay on board.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 10, the Immigration and Naturalization Service detained
the Texas Treasure to investigate the 133 crew members' immigration
status. That issue was resolved, as was the status of 55 foreign
nationals who boarded the ship later under temporary work visas.
</P>
<P>
   Now officials must determine if the cruise ship is registered in
the United States or another country. Under immigration law,
foreign ships must make foreign ports of call at least once every
29 days.
</P>
<P>
   Denton Lankford, an INS spokesman in San Antonio, said that
process could last through the week.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Lee, an attorney for the ship's owner, Las Vegas-based
Viva Gaming and Resorts Inc., said it should retain its temporary
foreign status, since similar gambling ship operations in Florida
and New York are not considered U.S. businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 0054 </TRAILER>
