<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $450M Sought for Polio Eradication  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The number of polio cases around the world
has plunged over the past 12 years, from at least 350,000 in 1988
to 7,000 last year and only 1,149 so far in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But stamping out the virus in the remaining 20 countries in
Africa and Asia will require access to war zones and $450 million,
World Health Organization Director-General Dr. Gro Harlem
Brundtland said Wednesday. About 30 countries had polio at the
start of 2000, she said, and the number is going down to 20 as the
new year approaches.
</P>
<P>
   At a summit of the public and private sector partners who have
been in the forefront of the global campaign to eradicate polio,
Brundtland launched a five-year plan to wipe out the disease by
2005 -- a target set in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for intensifying immunization activities against
polio, safely containing all laboratory stocks of the polio virus,
expanding routine immunizations, and agreeing on a timetable to
eventually end immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   For 10-year-old Thaddeus Farrow, who contracted polio in an
orphanage in India, eradication will be too late.
</P>
<P>
   But his mother, actress Mia Farrow, said they both dreamed of
living in a world where no child ever again suffers from the
disabling disease. She adopted Thaddeus five years ago and was
herself a child polio victim.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people could follow Thaddeus through just one day of his
life and see just how hard it is for him, I think there would be no
abstainees in saying 'let there be no more polio,''' she said,
describing his struggle to walk with braces.
</P>
<P>
   The final push to eradicate polio got a high-level endorsement
from Secretary-General Kofi Annan who warned that the ''race to
reach the last child ... is a race against time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do not seize the chance now, the virus will regain its
grip, and the opportunity will elude us forever -- or at least for a
very long time,'' he told some 250 summit participants.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging the commitment of the U.N. system to meet the 2005
target, Annan called for intensified efforts to negotiate access to
all children for national immunization days, particularly in
countries where fighting has disrupted health care systems, such as
Afghanistan and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala also
pledged support, issuing ''a call to arms to finish the job ... to
save millions of children from polio's tears, and millions of
parents from polio's fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Devlyn, president of Rotary International, and Ted Turner,
head of the United Nations Foundation, appealed to global
corporations and individual philanthropists for donations of $1
million or more to help raise the $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is estimated that the world will save $1.5 billion in
routine immunizations after polio is eradicated,'' said Devlyn.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, whose foundation donated $28 million, called on ''those
who have been blessed by more wealth than they need,'' to make
major contributions to the effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 0154 </TRAILER>
