<HEADLINE> Aussie Walker Booted From 20k Race  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- After walking for nearly 90 minutes,
Jane Saville could hear the roar of a jubilant hometown crowd
awaiting her entry into Olympic Stadium. Then the stadium suddenly
went silent.
</P>
<P>
   Saville had a comfortable lead in the 20-kilometer walk, and was
only about 150 meters from an Australian gold medal, when disaster
struck. A race judge waved a red card at Saville, signaling her
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   After entering the stadium tunnel in anticipation of a hero's
welcome, she turned around and walked away in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's bitterly disappointing, I thought I was going to win the
gold medal in my hometown,'' she said. ''I was thinking this is
going to be the most awesome experience of my life, and it was not
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Saville's disqualification allowed China's Wang Liping to
capture the gold medal. Kjersti Plaetzer of Norway won silver and
Maria Vasco of Spain took the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 20-kilometer walk last week, Mexico's Bernardo
Segura crossed the finish line first -- only to find out later he
had been disqualified. That gave the gold medal to Poland's Robert
Korzeniowski.
</P>
<P>
   Saville already had been given two white warning cards, and knew
a third ''lifting'' infraction -- not maintaining contact with the
ground -- would warrant a red card and automatic disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other leaders already had been disqualified.
Elisabetta Perrone of Italy continued to walk with Saville at the
front of the race even after getting a red card, but finally
stopped and walked off the course in the final kilometer.
</P>
<P>
   As Saville headed into the stadium tunnel, chief judge Lamberto
Vacchi suddenly pulled out his red card. Saville threw her arms in
the air and looked up in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'No, No, not me,'' she said. ''He said, 'Yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the stadium, where Saville's imminent arrival was being shown
on a jumbo video screen, there was a hush. Fans who had rushed to
the rail with cameras in hand put their heads down and walked
sullenly back to their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Saville did not continue walking through the tunnel, but headed
instead to a hill overlooking the stadium to look for her coach. A
half-hour later, she finally entered the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know what to do, I was quite embarrassed -- all these
people waiting for me in the stadium,'' she said. ''I could hear
the crowd in the tunnel, and my friends were at the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang won in 1 hour, 29 minutes, 5 seconds in the inaugural
20-kilometer walk for women at the Olympics. The event replaced the
10-kilometer walk that was contested at the 1992 and 1996 games.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Rohl was the top American in the race, finishing 17th
in 1:34.26. Chen Yueling, who won the 1992 gold medal in the
10-kilometer walk while competing for China and was granted
permission last month to compete for the United States, was 38th.
U.S. teammate Debbie Lawrence finished 44th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
