<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer on probation, friend arrested in stadium bottle-throwing incident </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Corrections officials will review a copy of the
complaint against Brian Peterson and a recommendation from his
parole officer before deciding if his arrest on a charge of
interfering with a police officer will have any effect on his
probation status.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, on probation for the 1996 killing of his newborn son,
was released on his own recognizance Wednesday after being
arraigned on the charge, which came after an arrest at Tuesday's
Mets game.
</P>
<P>
   A misdemeanor conviction would not necessarily mean his
probation would be revoked, said Beth Welch, a spokeswoman for the
Delaware Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything is possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, 22, pleaded innocent to the charge at the arraignment
in Queens criminal court. He was arrested Tuesday after a friend
allegedly threw a bottle at Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker and
he allegedly got in the way when police attempted to arrest the
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stephen Knopf chastised Peterson when talking to his
attorney, Russell Gioiella.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the media reports are correct, I hope your client realizes
the stupidity of his actions,'' Knopf said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody in Queens is more aware of the stupidity of his actions
than my client,'' Gioiella replied.
</P>
<P>
   The bottle landed about 10 feet from Rocker, who has been
vilified by New Yorkers since he disparaged them in a magazine
article last year.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Raymond Maniaci threw the bottle from the first-base
box seats. Maniaci, 22, of Wyckoff, N.J., was charged with reckless
endangerment. Peterson, also of Wyckoff, was charged with
obstructing governmental administration and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Maniaci was arraigned Wednesday after Peterson. He pleaded
innocent to the reckless endangerment charge and was released on
his own recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   News reports said that when police tried to arrest Maniaci,
Peterson got between them and his friend and refused to step away.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson told his mother, Barbara Zuchowski, that it was a
misunderstanding, that he was turning to step away as one officer
had instructed, his Delaware lawyer, Joseph Hurley, said after
talking to the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson pleaded guilty in 1998 to manslaughter - along with his
girlfriend, Amy Grossberg - in the November 1996 death of their
newborn son at a motel room in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson was given a two-year sentence, six months shorter than
Grossberg's, after he agreed to testify against her. He was
released from prison after serving 1&AMP;frac12; years and is currently
serving a two-year probation.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson also was sentenced to complete 300 hours of community
service and pay a $6,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said Peterson is required to inform his probation officer
if he is arrested and if he leaves New Jersey. She added that he
did receive permission to attend Tuesday's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
