<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GAO Reports on U.S. Nursing Homes  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two years after federal investigators found
serious care problems at many of the nation's 17,000 nursing homes,
a new government report cites progress but notes an increase in
homes with deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vigilance by both state and federal officials must be
unrelenting to ensure the safety and well-being of the nation's
nursing home residents,'' William Scanlon, director of health,
financing and public health issues for the General Accounting
Office said in testimony prepared for a hearing Thursday before the
Senate Special Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   The president two years ago announced a series of initiatives to
improve nursing homes after congressional hearings found
significant problems. The GAO, Congress' investigative arm, has
been monitoring the progress of those initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we've made some improvements, it still seems in many
ways we've been stuck in the same position since day one,'' said
Sen. John Breaux, a Louisiana Democrat who is the committee's
ranking member.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Sen. Chuck Grassley of Iowa, said
''These efforts must be sustained -- they must not be allowed to
falter -- in order for us to realize their potential for improved
nursing home care.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's investigation found a ''marginal increase
nationwide in the proportion of homes with documented actual
harm.'' Seventeen states had an increase of 5 percent or greater of
the number of homes with deficiencies. For instance, Arizona had
the highest increase, 19.6 percent, followed by Arkansas with a
16.1 percent increase and New York with a 14.3 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators said the results could be caused by several
things, including more rigorous efforts by states to identify
problems. ''The survey results could also suggest that nursing
homes may not have made sufficient strides to measurably improve
residents' quality care,'' Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for the change, Scanlon said it is
imperative that the Health Care Financing Administration, which
sets standards for nursing homes, continue to act.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the report noted that the health agency sometimes
lagged in its efforts to track how well states conducted surprise
visits.
</P>
<P>
   ''The performance of oversight can neither be taken for granted
nor relaxed, which means that neither HCFA nor the states can
afford to lose their current momentum,'' Scanlon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
