<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Refuses To Pressure Milosevic  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia will not join Western governments in their
call for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to step down after
Sunday's disputed election, Russia's foreign minister said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia won't pressure anyone in Yugoslavia,'' Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov said. ''This is an internal affair of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign leaders say Milosevic lost outright to challenger
Vojislav Kostunica, but Milosevic has defied calls to step down.
Yugoslavia's election commission says Kostunica got 48.96 of the
vote to 38.62 percent for Milosevic, necessitating a runoff because
neither won the required 50 percent. Kostunica, using figures from
opposition poll watchers, maintains he got 52.54 percent to
Milosevic's 32.01 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While Western countries have dismissed the talk of a runoff and
urged Milosevic to concede defeat, Moscow has warned other
governments to stay out of Yugoslav affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Russia vehemently opposed the NATO-led bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia last year, and has repeatedly welcomed Yugoslav
officials to Moscow. But it has shown signs of trying to distance
itself from Milosevic in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian election observer returning from Yugoslavia,
Konstantin Kosachov, said Thursday that the elections were ''normal
and democratic,'' the Interfax news agency reported. Kosachov is
deputy head of the lower house of parliament's international
affairs committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boris Nemtsov, the leader of the liberal Union of
Right Forces faction in the lower house of Russian parliament, said
the government must pressure Milosevic to make the runoff fair.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Moscow makes no effort, the election in Yugoslavia will be
falsified,'' Nemtsov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
