<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher Thursday in a tentative
change of direction after a week of mostly down trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 28.48 at 10,656.84.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite rose
3.31 to 3,659.61 and the Standard and Poor's 500 stock-index
climbed 3.84 to 1,430.41.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have been down for most of September on market worries
about corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The market has swung up and down, as investors, unsure where to
put their money, have punished stocks of companies that even hint
at disappointing results when third-quarter earnings are announced
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the stress are energy prices at decade-high levels
and a weak European currency -- all factors that many companies say
will hurt their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   This week's slump has been across the board with particular
emphasis on two sectors: Internet companies and telecomm suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   That trend appeared to continue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Networks, which makes telecom equipment, fell $1.03 to
$28.25 in early trading, extending a decline that began the
previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Discount travel Web site Priceline also slipped again, down 13
cents to $10.63, after losing more than 40 percent of its value
Wednesday when it warned about weak corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.03 at 508.10.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.08 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.76 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 0.83 percent, and France's CAC-40 dropped
0.50 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
