<DOCNO> APW20000928.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Church Backs Milosevic Opponent  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Opposition leader Vojislav Kostunica
gained the critical endorsement of the Serbian Orthodox Church on
Thursday and his supporters threatened a general strike to force
Slobodan Milosevic to recognize their election victory.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, however, confirmed Thursday that he will take part in
a runoff after finishing second to Kostunica in Sunday's
presidential election. Summoning his closest Socialist Party
associates, Milosevic focused on ''immediate tasks'' ahead of the
second round, the state-run Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition discussions about calling a general strike -- shutting
down schools, offices and other public institutions until Milosevic
steps aside -- come amid efforts to ratchet up the pressure on
Milosevic to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica earned 48.96 percent of the vote to 38.62 percent for
Milosevic, the State Election Commission said late Wednesday. That
would require a runoff Oct. 8. The opposition, using figures from
its poll watchers, claims Kostunica won 52.54 percent to
Milosevic's 32.01 percent -- which would mean he won outright.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica's campaign manager, Zoran Djindjic, called the
government tally ''a bad joke.'' He vowed to take the opposition
beyond street protests -- which have been unsuccessful -- by calling
''a total blockade of the system and institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will call a general strike,'' Djindjic said. ''We shall
seek to paralyze all institutions, schools, theaters, cinemas,
offices ... call everyone onto the streets and stay on the streets
until he who wants to be president by force gives up his post.''
</P>
<P>
   The influential Serbian Orthodox Church recognized Kostunica's
election victory and addressed him as ''president-elect.'' The
church holds no direct political power in Yugoslavia, but its
dictates hold great moral sway in a population which recognizes it
as a pillar of rectitude in a corrupt society.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the pressure on Milosevic to step down, European
Union officials said Thursday the 15 EU members will not back a
second round. In Brussels, EU officials said the organization will
hold off, for now, on lifting economic and other sanctions against
Serbia until Kostunica has been installed as president.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the days ahead you will see the EU nations treating
Kostunica as the president-elect'' of Yugoslavia, said one EU
foreign policy official.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, the official said Sunday's
elections signaled ''the end of the regime'' of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But in Moscow, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said that
Russia will not join western governments in their call for
Milosevic to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia won't pressure anyone in Yugoslavia,'' Ivanov said.
''This is an internal affair of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Key officials in Kostunica's coalition conducted emergency
talks. In a statement issued afterward they pledged to ''defend the
truth and the democratic will of our people,'' but failed to
outline any specific strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that ''Vojislav Kostunica was elected Yugoslav
president in the first round of the elections,'' the opposition
leaders once again called on the members of the State Electoral
Commission to ''publicly acknowledge the true election results.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments came the morning after more than 200,000 joyful
Milosevic opponents swarmed the capital's downtown district, waving
banners and chanting ''He's finished.'' There was no visible police
presence near the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   An opposition member of the electoral commission said the head
of the body presented the 13 members with just before midnight --
shortly after the crowds had scattered for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition members were not allowed them to inspect the returns,
but the commission voted to approve them, 10-3.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the election commission reportedly resigned from
their posts, due to ''pressures they were under to falsify the
results,'' media reported. Among them was Bojan Pudar, the deputy
head of the commission, FoNet news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinisa Nikolic said 300 of the more than 10,000 polling stations
never reported, and he accused the commission of reducing the
overall total by 600,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and other Western leaders have dismissed talk
of a runoff. ''The government's official election commission has no
credibility whatever,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
said the United States will move to lift economic sanctions against
Yugoslavia and restore its rights as a U.N. member state if
Kostunica is installed in Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 1047 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000928.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow up 22; Nasdaq Down 30  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chips were higher but technology issues
lagged Thursday as ongoing worries about corporate profits
frustrated the market's efforts to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 21.82 at 10,650.18.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 0.63 at 1,427.20, but the Nasdaq composite index fell
29.75 to 3,626.55.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have been down for most of September on market worries
about corporate profits. And investors, unsure where to put their
money, have punished stocks of companies that even hint at
disappointing results when third-quarter earnings are announced
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the stress are energy prices at decade-high levels
and a weak European currency -- all factors that many companies say
will hurt their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   This week's slump has been across the board with particular
emphasis on two sectors: Internet companies and telecomm suppliers.
But there were signs of that trend weakening Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which makes telecom equipment, fell $1.44 to
$55.88. Nortel Networks was down 28 cents at $59, extending a
decline that began the previous session. But Lucent moved higher,
trading up $1.19 to $29.75.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com slipped 38 cents to $37.50. Priceline, the discount
travel Web site, was down 6 cents at $10.69 after losing more than
40 percent of its value Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   News of a $6.5 billion merger between Global Crossing and
Exodus, two Web site hosting companies, had mixed results on the
Nasdaq. Exodus fell $5.75 to $47.50 in morning trading; Global
Crossing was up $1.44 at $31.31.
</P>
<P>
   A new videogame console helped push Sony up $1.50 to $100.88 on
the New York Stock Exchange, despite the company's warning that its
component shortages will affect initial shipments to North America.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 127,67 million
shares, agead if 135.87 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.79 at 508.92.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.08 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.76 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 0.83 percent, and France's CAC-40 dropped
0.50 percent.
</P>
