<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 109; Nasdaq Adds 68  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks shot higher Thursday, buoyed by rebounds
in technology and blue chip issues, as the market appeared to find
its footing despite ongoing worries about corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The advance came despite a new report showing the U.S. economy
growing at the fastest rate since the fourth quarter of 1999, and
well ahead of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 109.13 at 10,737.49. The Dow had fallen in each of
the first three sessions this week.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 23.77 at 1,450.34, and the Nasdaq composite index
rose 68.49 to 3,724.79.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Nie, a technical analyst at First Union Securities, didn't
see any one driving force behind the market's behavior. He said of
the Dow, ''you simply have 23 issues up and only seven down, and
that's better news.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have been down for most of September on worries about
corporate profits. And investors have punished stocks of companies
that even hint at disappointing results when third-quarter results
are announced next month.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the stress are energy prices at decade-high levels
and a weak European currency -- factors that many companies say will
hurt their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   A Commerce Department report released Thursday raised new
questions about whether the Federal Reserve's efforts to slow
growth to a more sustainable level have worked.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, which showed the economy expanding at a rate of
5.6 percent between April and June, a faster rate than the 4.8
percent growth in the first three months of 2000, didn't seem to
cause much concern on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again concentrated on corporate earnings, although
their reactions weren't consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble jumped $4.31 to $66.19 after the consumer
products manufacturer said it would meet Wall Street expectations
for the third quarter after several disappointing quarters. But
investors unloaded Safeway, trading it down $3.63 to $50.50,
although the grocery store chain reported profits in line with
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Internet and telecom stocks appeared to be recovering Thursday
from their slump.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which makes telecom equipment, fell 13 cents to
$57.19 after it was downgraded by a Sanford Bernstein analyst. But
competitor Nortel Networks rose $3.28 to $62.56, halting a decline
that began the previous session. Lucent also moved higher, trading
up $2.88 at $31.44.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed Hewlett Packard up $2.94 to $105.75.
</P>
<P>
   And Web portal Yahoo! was up $6.13 at $96.50, gaining back half
of its loss Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   News of a $6.5 billion merger between Global Crossing and
Exodus, two Web site hosting companies, had mixed results. Exodus
fell $2 to $51.25, after slumping more than $5 in morning trading.
Global Crossing was up $2.38 at $32.25.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 514.64 million
shares, behind the 523.26 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 7.33 at 515.46.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
