<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Makes Deals as Budget Looms  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, with just three days before the
Oct. 1 start of fiscal 2001, pushed through a spending bill
providing about $23.6 billion for energy and water projects.
</P>
<P>
   As the House passed the bill on a 301-118 vote, lawmakers were
conferring with administration officials on other spending
legislation, trying to nail down deals on easing trade sanctions
against Cuba and creating a new land conservation program sought by
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two of the 13 annual spending measures for next
year have become law. The energy bill faces a veto threat because
it would block the administration from moving toward allowing a
seasonal surge in the Missouri River to protect endangered birds
and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats from the Northeast also protested the decision to
remove a provision in the House-passed version of the bill that
would have set up a 2-million-barrel home-heating-oil reserve to
deal with winter hardships in that region.
</P>
<P>
   That same provision would have reauthorized the president's
power to withdraw oil from the 600-million-barrel Strategic
Petroleum Reserve. President Clinton has announced plans to tap 30
million barrels from that reserve to check rising oil prices, a
move Republicans have criticized as aimed at winning political
points before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., said Republicans killed the reserve
proposal when people in his area are ''facing the worst winter
heating crisis in two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Ron Packard, R-Calif., chairman of the House
Appropriations energy and water subcommittee, said the proposal was
removed from the final bill because matters dealing with fossil
fuels were the jurisdiction of a different panel handling Interior
Department spending.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the Missouri River pits environmental concerns
against opposition by farm and shipping interests -- as well as
members of both parties from Missouri, a swing state in the
presidential race. Among the opponents of changing the river's flow
are Gov. Mel Carnahan, the Democratic Senate candidate, and House
Democratic leader Dick Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ''That would be a serious error,'' Sen. Kit Bond, R-Mo., who
wants to leave the river's controlled flows unaltered, said of a
Clinton veto.
</P>
<P>
   White House budget chief Jack Lew told reporters that ''we were
as clear as we could be'' about vetoing the overall bill if the
Missouri River language remained.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetening the energy and water bill were dozens of new projects
that lawmakers squeezed in, including $24 million for flood control
and cleanup projects in Kentucky won by Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with the certainty that most spending bills won't be
approved by midnight Saturday, the Senate prepared to approve a
measure keeping federal agencies open through Oct. 6. That is
expected to be the first of several stopgap measures to avoid a
federal shutdown while budget talks continue.
</P>
<P>
   The energy and water measure -- $1.9 billion larger than the
version the House approved in June -- is one of many spending bills
whose price tags are swelling because of demands from the Clinton
administration and lawmakers from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Another, the $18 billion Interior Department bill, is $3 billion
bigger than the version the House approved.
</P>
<P>
   To it, White House and congressional bargainers were hoping to
add a compromise multibillion-dollar land conservation program.
Still unclear were the exact cost and the specific programs it
could be used for, but the emerging measure was sure to be smaller
than a 15-year, $45 billion version the House overwhelmingly
approved in May.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also objected to some environmental
provisions in the Interior bill. Republicans were ready to drop
language, opposed by Clinton, easing environmental protections for
New Hampshire's White Mountains and Colorado's White River, aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate agriculture measure, GOP leaders agreed among
themselves to partly lift food and drug trade sanctions against
Cuba by letting U.S. financial institutions help arrange
third-country financing of such sales, said Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how widespread support for the plan was. But
partially easing the 37-year-old sanctions would end a lengthy
battle between congressional foes of Cuban leader Fidel Castro, a
coalition of farm-state lawmakers who want more trade, and liberals
and conservatives who say such trade is the best way to loosen
Communism's grip on the Caribbean nation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also were moving toward easing restrictions on
importing U.S.-made drugs from overseas, where they often sell for
less. They also were ready to include $3.5 billion to help farmers
hurt by fires, drought and other problems, said House
Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The agriculture bill was expected to exceed $75 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 1306 </TRAILER>
