<DOCNO> APW20000928.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Times Critiques Lee Coverage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For the second time this week, The New York
Times has critiqued its own writings about the Wen Ho Lee nuclear
secrets case -- this time on its editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial that took up two full columns on the editorial
page Thursday, the newspaper said it had reviewed the editorials it
had published over the past 17 months about the fired Los Alamos
scientist and security at the New Mexico lab.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of the main arguments have held up well,'' the editorial
said, ''although with the benefit of hindsight we find that we too
quickly accepted the government's theory that espionage was the
main reason for Chinese nuclear advances and its view that Dr. Lee
had been properly singled out as the prime suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, was released last month from nine months of solitary
confinement after pleading guilty to one count of mishandling
nuclear secrets and agreeing to tell what he did with the
information he admits downloading onto tapes and unsecure
computers.
</P>
<P>
   He originally had been charged with 59 counts of breaching
national security.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh and Attorney General Janet Reno have
defended the government's case, most recently before the Senate
Select Intelligence and Judiciary committees.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh told the senators Tuesday the prosecution would likely
have succeeded at trial, but he said a trial would have exposed
nuclear secrets and might not have revealed what happened to the
downloaded information.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh also have denied accusations that Lee, a
Taiwanese-born naturalized U.S. citizen, was targeted because of
his race.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1,680-word editors note on Tuesday, the Times acknowledged
there were flaws in its coverage. Although the note defended the
work of its reporters and said that ''on the whole, we remain proud
of work that bought into the open a major national security
problem,'' it criticized decisions by ''those who directed the
coverage, for not raising questions that occurred to us only
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a memo to the newspaper's staff that followed
publication of the editors note, Times Managing Editor Bill Keller
stressed that the phrase ''those who directed the coverage'' was
referring to himself and Executive Editor Joseph Lelyveld -- not to
the editors who directly supervised the stories.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe and I have tried to make clear in meetings with staff what
seemed obvious to us,'' Keller wrote, ''that the paragraph referred
to ourselves -- not just in the general, the-buck-stops-here, way,
but in the very specific sense that we laid our hands on these
articles, and we overlooked some opportunities in our own direction
of the coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's piece faulted the editorial page's past conclusions
that China's critical expertise on miniaturization of warheads was
''most likely'' stolen from lab computers.
</P>
<P>
   It also said the editorials ''may have been overly sharp'' in
questioning the fitness of national security adviser Samuel R.
Berger and in criticizing Reno for refusing to approve a wiretap on
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial said that although the paper had warned about the
dangers of racial profiling in Lee's case, ''we should have looked
more searchingly at the conditions under which he was confined and
the government's arguments for denial of bail.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial said the importance of the nuclear weapons issue
to national security warrants aggressive reporting and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   It noted that Lee had been investigated for more than three
years before the newspaper published its first articles, and that
nuclear weapons security and transfer of technology to China had
been constant government concerns during this time.
</P>
<P>
   ''To withhold this information from readers is an unthinkable
violation of the fundamental contract between a newspaper and its
audience. The only choice is to bring that information forward in
news and opinion columns in a professionally careful, self-critical
way,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
