<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Air Force on Alert at Glacier  </HEADLINE>
By AJIT KUMAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEH, India (AP) -- Despite five layers of clothing, paratroopers
shiver as they wait to board an air force transport at the world's
highest air base.
</P>
<P>
   The AN-32A planes approach the stark runway at Leh in snowy
mist, pushed by tail winds. The pilots navigate the steep mountains
by sight.
</P>
<P>
   Higher on the icy Himalayan peaks, helicopter pilots battle
downdrafts as they land on helipads to deliver precious supplies or
rescue injured soldiers. The pilots stay on the ground no more than
30 seconds for fear of being shot.
</P>
<P>
   This is life on the 20,000-foot-high Siachen Glacier, the
world's highest battleground. Hundreds of Pakistani and Indian
soldiers face off, and often fire at each other, on the chunks of
ice.
</P>
<P>
   But cold kills more troops than bullets. Soldiers brought down
to base camp often suffer hearing, eyesight and memory loss because
of prolonged use of oxygen masks. Many lose eyes, hands or feet to
frostbite.
</P>
<P>
   Since India drove back Pakistan-based fighters in the Kargil
sector of Kashmir last year, the Indian military has been focusing
on Siachen to ward off another intrusion in the Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian military was caught off guard in May 1999 when it
discovered that combatants had crossed a cease-fire line running
along the tops of mountains in Kashmir to occupy positions that
brought an Indian national highway within reach of Pakistani guns.
</P>
<P>
   India says it fought Pakistani soldiers for the next 11 weeks,
while Pakistan's government said the fighters were indigenous
Kashmiris opposed to Indian control of the mostly Muslim region.
</P>
<P>
   The Kargil fighting showed India that the most uninhabitable,
frozen land was not a sufficient barrier to intrusion. The Indian
air force, trying to show that it is on the alert in a region even
harder to defend than the sheer Kargil cliffs, has arranged a
series of trips for photojournalists to see the Siachen operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Particularly since the Kargil war, the load of responsibility
of the air force has increased,'' Air Vice Marshal S.K. Jain told
journalists during a tour Tuesday. ''The forces are on alert, ready
to meet any threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound of incoming gunfire could be heard as the air force
transports loaded up at Leh, on the approach to the Siachen
Glacier.
</P>
<P>
   The last major gunbattle in the region was reported Sept. 4,
1999, when India said Pakistani artillery and mortar fire killed
nine Indian soldiers on the craggy slopes of Turtuk, near the
47-mile-long Siachen Glacier.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and India have disputed the border at Siachen since the
first cease-fire line was drawn after their 1947-48 war. It was
only in 1984 that the Indian army sent a battalion to occupy the
glacier.
</P>
<P>
   Some army posts on the peaks are only 1,000 feet from Pakistani
entrenchments. Cheetah helicopters fly in to retrieve wounded or
sick soldiers and drop supplies to their comrades, who remain
behind on the lonely promontories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
