<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Plans to Cut 350,000 Troops  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID McHUGH
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A top Russian general on Thursday reaffirmed plans
make deep cuts in Russia's military, saying the country no longer
has the money for such a large force.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions, to be made over 2001-2003, would cut 350,000
troops from the estimated 1.2 million people serving under the
Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Vladislav Putilin, who heads the general staff's main
organizational and mobilization department, said: ''We are in a
situation in which external military perils have diminished and the
state is unable to fully finance the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Therefore the reduction of armed forces personnel is
inevitable, and the armed forces command regards this as an
objective need,'' Putilin was quoted as saying by the Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, President Vladimir Putin said that there would be
no ''hasty or wholesale'' cuts in the number of soldiers and that
more time was needed to plan military reform.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin didn't reject cuts and insisted the country's military
was too unwieldy and had to be modernized.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts were first announced by Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
earlier this month, but few details have been made public.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Defense Ministry troops, Russia has hundreds of
thousands of more troops spread across several agencies, including
intelligence services, the Interior Ministry, the Border Guards,
and even the railroad forces.
</P>
<P>
   Russian news media have reported, without naming sources, that
there are plans for broader cuts of 600,000 across the entire
military establishment of more than 2 million troops and about 1
million civilian workers.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's leaders have been vowing to reform the military for
years, but haven't followed through. Plans to end the draft and to
move to a professional army fell by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   Planes can't fly and ships are mothballed for lack of fuel and
maintenance, new weapons are not bought and new soldiers are not
thoroughly trained -- or even regularly fed.
</P>
<P>
   The military suffered a stinging humiliation in Chechnya, where
several thousand lightly armed independence fighters drove out
Russian troops in 1996. Russian forces retook most of the region in
an operation that began last year, but have suffered high
casualties and haven't ended rebel resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Putin acknowledged there had been ''objections'' from commanders
to plans to cut the number of soldiers. Some Russian military and
political officials are clearly nostalgic for the Soviet Union's
superpower status and its large forces that confronted NATO during
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Russia's lagging economy doesn't generate
enough money to support a large army. Russia's defense budget is
about $5.1 billion, compared with annual U.S. defense spending of
around $290 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
