<HEADLINE> African Leader Accused of Lie  </HEADLINE>
Junta leader accused of circulating forged marriage certificate
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department accused the Ivory Coast
military government of circulating a falsified U.S. marriage
certificate of a prominent politician in an effort to bar him from
challenging Gen. Robert Guei in a presidential election next month.
</P>
<P>
   The department said in a statement Thursday it was ''greatly
concerned but not surprised'' the falsified document was used as a
pretext to disqualify Guei's main rival, Alassane Ouattara, a
former prime minister and executive of the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Guei says Ouattara is ineligible because his family was
originally from neighboring Burkina Faso. The government claimed
Ouattara listed his father's residence as Upper Volta, which is now
Burkina Faso, in filling out a marriage certificate as a student in
Philadelphia in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said the people of Ivory Coast should be
able to choose a president freely, but that it was not surprised
that Guei, who came to power in a military coup, was trying to
manipulate the election with a false marriage certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Guei took power last December. He has accused Ouattara of
plotting to assassinate him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
