<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Million Marooned by Floods  </HEADLINE>
By RAMOLA TALWAR BADAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   AISTHALA, India (AP) -- Steering clear of bloated corpses and
poisonous snakes, flood survivors wade through chest-high water in
eastern India, searching for lost relatives and valuables.
</P>
<P>
   Jackals and vultures move in and there is no place for
cremations or burials in the aftermath of 10 days of torrential
rain that have killed about 1,000 people and marooned millions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw many bodies floating. Some people tied stones to the
corpses to sink the bodies because there was no place to bury
them,'' said Basanti Das, 35, who weaves saris by hand in Aisthala
village, 45 miles north of Calcutta. ''There is so much water all
around, where is the place to cremate anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after unseasonable monsoon rains forced rivers to
overflow across eastern India and western Bangladesh, people --
joined by their goats and dogs -- are still living on the roofs of
their mud and brick houses to guard against thieves who row up in
boats to loot abandoned homes.
</P>
<P>
   In India, 651 people are known to have died in the floods, and
225 are missing and presumed dead. In Bangladesh, 57 have died. A
total of 18 million in both countries are believed to be marooned.
Millions more have seen their meager homes washed away.
</P>
<P>
   The floods began Sept. 18 when late rains mixed with the melting
snows of the Himalayas, forcing water to overflow the banks of the
Ganges, Hoogly, Bhagirathi and other major rivers. While they wait
for the rain to stop and the water to run off into the Bay of
Bengal, millions are living on small patches of mud or rooftops
that have become islands in a swirling brown sea.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Nishchintapur, 160 miles north of Calcutta,
vultures hover and then swoop down. Packs of jackals can be seen
feasting on carcasses of animals as the waters begin to recede.
</P>
<P>
   Das, the sari weaver, says she and her husband and three sons
swam from their sinking home, leaving everything behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I wear now is given in charity at the relief camps,'' she
said. ''We had to leave our house once snakes started coming in.
There were big snakes on the roof and in the cooking room. They
came looking for shelter the night of the floods.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers from World Vision and the Missionaries of
Charity, the religious order of women founded by Mother Teresa,
confirmed that at least 50 of the 200 deaths in the area were due
to snake bites.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Calcutta, with an official population of 13 million,
have been inundated as well, as the Hoogly River overflowed into
canals running through the city, knocking aside sandbags and
seeping into homes and shops.
</P>
<P>
   Floods are rare in western Bangladesh, but this year, the
tree-lined frontier between the two countries has become a sea of
water overflowing from the Indian rivers. Railroad lines and roads
have been submerged and the main truck hub for transporting goods
between India and Bangladesh was under water.
</P>
<P>
   In Ranaghat, the only relatively dry town in Nadia district
north of Calcutta, those who spend the nights on rooftops wade at
daybreak to the relief camps set up on muddy fields to get food and
water.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been staying on the roof of our neighbor's home for
eight days. I can't see my house anymore, but I'm waiting for the
water to ebb to see if anything can be recovered,'' said Noni
Gopal, a shopkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people crowd around relief workers distributing
rice and brown sugar wrapped in banana leaves and newspapers. The
survivors form huge circles, squatting on the dirt and scooping out
the food with their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are so many people. Who knows if the food will be
enough?'' worries Gita Deb, a farm laborer.
</P>
<P>
   Tube wells have been dug and medicine dispensaries set up near
relief camps in schools and abandoned factories in Ranaghat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Human waste is seeping from the submerged homes into the
surrounding water and with so many people swimming back and forth,
there is always the fear of disease,'' said Shakuntala Dias, a nun
in the white and blue robes of the Missionaries of Charity.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 people pack into each classroom of the schools
turned into relief camps. Clothes hand to dry near the windows. The
corridors are lined with charred wood as women cook rice in
blackened pots.
</P>
<P>
   Others crouch in plastic tents propped up by bamboo sticks
outside the crowded camps.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 people in one camp share 20 makeshift toilets put
together with bamboo and sack cloth.
</P>
<P>
   People move between their sunken homes and the camps by rowing
wooden boats or paddling inflated tyres. Children watched from
rooftops as two young boys perched on a huge iron cooking pot
steered home, ferrying food in cloth bags.
</P>
<P>
   In villages like Aisthala, men swept the rooftops clean of
fallen leaves even as the brown flood water lapped at the lower
levels of their houses. They do not want to leave. All they want is
for the water to ebb so that they can re-enter their homes, find
what is left and rebuild what is broken.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very scared when the water came rushing in that night,''
said Das' 8-year-old son, Rupa. ''But now I want to go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 1516 </TRAILER>
