<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brandenburg Gate Gets a Facelift  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Decades of grime will soon be stripped from the
Brandenburg Gate, the first cleanup for Berlin's best-known emblem
since before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration experts will use lasers to get rid of black deposits
and seal cracks on the 211-year-old sandstone arch, which survived
two world wars but has straddled a major traffic axis since the
Berlin Wall dividing east and west came down in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors will finance the facelift's cost of up to
$5.5 million, the historic monuments foundation in charge of the
project said Thursday. The restoration is due to start next month
and is expected to take at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The gate, 213 feet wide and 66 feet high, was part of the Berlin
Wall during Germany's Cold War division into capitalist west and
communist east. It became the symbol of reunited Germany after the
wall fell -- and especially after parliament moved back into the
nearby Reichstag building last year as part of the government's
return to Berlin from Bonn, the former West German capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
