<HEADLINE> Business Briefs from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE BROOK, N.J. (AP) - EluSys Therapeutics Inc. will
collaborate with the U.S. Army Medical Research Institute of
Infectious Diseases to develop treatments for anthrax and other
potential biowarfare agents, EluSys has announced.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement announced Wednesday, EluSys and the Army will
develop antibodies to principal anthrax toxins that will be
incorporated into EluSys' heteropolymer technology.
</P>
<P>
   EluSys and the Army hope to develop compounds that will prevent
the disease before exposure and treat those who have been exposed.
</P>
<P>
   NEWTOWN, Pa. (AP) - EduNeering Inc., which provides online
training for businesses, will move its headquarters from Newtown to
Princeton, N.J., the company announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   EduNeering also announced it has merged with KnowledgeWire LLC
of Houston, a developer of online training solutions for business
and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delamontague, founder of EduNeering, will be chief
executive officer of the new company. William Lidwell, who was
president and CEO of KnowledgeWire, will become chief technology
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Current EduNeering customers include Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the Food
and Drug Administration and Premera Blue Cross. General Electric is
among KnowledgeWire's current customers.
</P>
<P>
   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) - The U.S. Army has awarded a three-year,
$196 million contract to a Honeywell-General Electric partnership
to develop, produce and test gas-turbine engines for the Crusader
self-propelled artillery system and as a retrofit for the M1 Abrams
battle tank.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell made the announcement Thursday. Revenues will be
divided equally between Honeywell and GE. The contract pertains to
24 LV100-5 engines.
</P>
<P>
   Under a separate second phase, the partnership expects to
produce 3,400 engines, 2,700 for the Abrams tanks beginning in
2004, and 720 for the Crusaders beginning in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The engines will provide rapid acceleration and will start
quickly, even in cold climates.
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Journal Register Co. has promoted Thomas E.
Rice to senior vice president for operations, Journal Register
Chairman Robert M. Jelenic announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rice joined Journal Register in 1988 as general manager of
Suburban Newspapers of Greater St. Louis Inc., and more recently
served as president of Sunrise Industries Inc. and president and
chief executive officer of Suburban Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Rice takes assumes his new role in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Journal Register Co. owns 151 nondaily publications and 25 daily
newspapers, including The Trentonian of Trenton and the New Haven
(Conn.) Register.
</P>
<P>
   PLAINSBORO, N.J. (AP) - Pharmaceutical maker Bristol-Myers
Squibb has donated 29 heart defibrillators to law enforcement
agencies in Middlesex, Mercer, Somerset and Union counties.
</P>
<P>
   The company officials said the devices, which administer an
electric shock to the heart to reverse sudden changes in or
cessations of heart rhythm, were donated to towns where
Bristol-Myers Squibb facilities are located.
</P>
<P>
   Those towns are: Cranbury, Edison, Hamilton, Hillside, Hopewell,
Lawrence, Montgomery, New Brunswick, North Brunswick, Pennington
Borough, Plainsboro and West Windsor. The Mercer County Sheriff's
Department also received a defibrillator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
