<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio backtracks on upstate economy  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio backtracked Thursday on his
earlier suggestions that the struggling western New York economy
had turned the corner.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Rotary Club here, Lazio noted that over the
last 18 months, the region had seen a net job gain of about 11,000
jobs. But he pointedly added, ''I know that the recovery here
hasn't reached every single family.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone in the audience suggested that he might be a
different kind of carpetbagger who would forget western New York
once the election against Democratic opponent Hillary Rodham
Clinton was over, Lazio said: ''I don't think of Long Island as my
home. I think of New York as my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican Senate candidate, had been criticized by
Clinton's campaign, the Buffalo News editorial page and even some
Republicans for painting a rosy picture of the upstate economy
during the debate in Buffalo two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also criticized the National Abortion Rights Action League
of New York, which said Thursday that it intends to violate the
soft-money ban reached by Lazio and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's in the spirit of the agreement. I think
Mrs. Clinton should condemn it,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Conlin, head of NARAL-NY, said Thursday that the ban on
television and radio ads paid for by outside groups in the Senate
campaign ''is a violation of our First Amendment rights to free
speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Conlin showed a TV ad the group has produced criticizing Lazio's
stands on abortion rights. NARAL-NY has not yet bought air time for
the ad, but Conlin said eventually it would.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL-NY has endorsed Clinton, and bought air time earlier in
the campaign for a different anti-Lazio ad.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Clinton and Lazio made a deal prohibiting their
respective political parties from using unregulated campaign
donations to purchase TV and radio ads to boost their candidacies.
Both Clinton and Lazio asked other independent groups to abide by
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Conlin said her group is ''not beholden to any candidate.
... Our purpose is to preserve abortion rights.''
</P>
<P>
   NARAL-NY is nonpartisan. Before Lazio entered the race, the
group had declined to make an endorsement because the previous
Republican candidate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, was considered by
NARAL to have as strong a record on abortion rights as Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has repeatedly said that he supports abortion rights, but
he has voted against Medicaid funding for abortion for low-income
women, and more significantly for abortion-rights supporters, Lazio
has said he would not use Roe v. Wade as a litmus test in approving
Supreme Court justices. Clinton has committed to voting only for
nominees to the high court who vow to uphold abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign manager Bill deBlasio said the campaign sent
NARAL a letter Wednesday asking the group ''to respect the
agreement that we came to, reminding them that it's something
Hillary cares about deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokeswoman Cathie Levine added that ''NARAL has a lot
at stake in this election and we appreciate that to date they have
abided by Hillary's request.''
</P>
<P>
   Until NARAL buys the air time, it has not technically broken the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's campaign unveiled a new statewide ad that
began airing Thursday. The ad touted Clinton's tax-cut initiatives
and bashed Lazio's tax plan as a clone of Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-money ban does not apply to ads the campaigns
themselves produce using so-called hard money, which consists of
$1,000 individual donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
