<HEADLINE> Third man pleads in connection with slaying of elderly women  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) - A 19-year-old man admitted Wednesday he
was the lookout during a 1998 burglary that ended with the
bludgeoning death of two elderly widows.
</P>
<P>
   Because Terrance T. Townsend is a first-time offender,
prosecutors allowed a plea to a reduced burglary charge that will
mean four years in prison instead of the 15 he had faced in
connection with the murders of Matilda Montenaro, 84, and her
80-year-old sister-in-law Lois DiMaria.
</P>
<P>
   The woman were beaten to death Dec. 16, 1998 after a botched
burglary by Aaron Umber and George Johnson. Umber and Johnson also
tried to burn down the house after the killings, lighting a fire
and turning on the gas stove.
</P>
<P>
   Umber, 22, pleaded guilty to two counts of second-degree murder
and related charges of robbery, burglary and arson in exchange for
40 years to life in prison. Johnson, 20, was sentenced to 80 years
to life following a trial on murder, burglary and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe a fourth man was involved but have not yet
charged him.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend will be sentenced Nov. 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
