<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. tightens PCB standards for ocean dumping of dredge spoils  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The federal government on Thursday announced
tighter restrictions on the amount of toxic PCBs in dredge spoils
to be dumped off prime New Jersey beaches, a step environmentalists
said should have come sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've waited over three years. Unfortunately for the ocean,
over a million tons of mud has been dumped out there that shouldn't
have,'' said Cindy Zipf, executive director of Clean Ocean Action,
based on Sandy Hook.
</P>
<P>
   The new standards for cancer-causing PCBs (polychlorinated
biphenyl), apply to a thick, gooey material scraped from the bottom
of New York-New Jersey Harbor's tributaries to ensure sufficient
depth for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The standards came in an agreement between the Environmental
Protection Agency and the Army Corps of Engineers that set a limit
of 113 parts per billion, down from 400, in worms. The level for
clams remains 100.
</P>
<P>
   Sea life is tested to determine how much contamination is moving
up the food chain, said Mary Mears, spokeswoman for the
Environmental Protection Agency. For example, worms are eaten by
fish, which are later eaten by humans.
</P>
<P>
   The creatures are tested after spending four weeks in a sample
of spoils that is being proposed for ocean dumping, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also provides that the public can comment on what
standards ought to be applied for 60 other chemicals that can be
found in dredge spoils.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one-third of the solution,'' said Andrew Willner,
baykeeper of New York-New Jersey harbor, an affiliate of the
American Littoral Society.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other two-thirds are pollution prevention and aggressive
prosecution of polluters, and overall port planning. The New
York-New Jersey harbor, which is very shallow, may not be the
appropriate port for very large ships.''
</P>
<P>
   The directive is the latest milestone in the continuing clash of
competing interests: environmentalists seeking to mitigate a
century of offshore toxic dumping, and commercial interests that
contend the shipping channels must be deepened or the ever-larger
vessels that ply the harbor will take their business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest method for disposing spoils is ocean dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, only sludge largely free of contaminants was to be
placed in an area three to six miles off Sandy Hook, part of which
is called the Mud Dump.
</P>
<P>
   The ''clean'' material was to be used to cover the
15-square-mile Historic Area Remediation Site, the result of nearly
100 years of dumping that has left an underwater pile of muck that
at one point rises seven stories from the ocean floor, Zipf said.
</P>
<P>
   ''EPA was using a definition of uncontaminated that was not
uncontaminated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a huge toxic stain off our coast that we've got to
fix. And the only way to fix it is to put a clean Band-Aid over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   About eight dumping projects in the past two years would not
have met the new standard, including spoils from the Brooklyn
(N.Y.) Marine Terminal and Raritan River in central New Jersey,
said Rep. Frank J. Pallone Jr., D-Long Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Castle Astoria Terminals, an oil shipper in Queens, N.Y., has
already received permits to begin dumping 100,000 tons of spoils
next month, which Pallone conceded can proceed even though the
material would not qualify under the tougher standard.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman, whose district includes Sandy Hook, said he
would seek money so that Castle Astoria can dispose of the dredged
material on land.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman on Thursday said she would make some of
the state's on-land dumping space available for New York spoils.
</P>
<P>
   No permit has been issued for U.S. Gypsum, which is seeking to
dump 107,000 tons of dredged material from the Hudson River in New
York. Those spoils do not meet the new standards and should not be
allowed, Pallone said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cleanoceanaction.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.epa.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://www.usace.army.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1540 </TRAILER>
