<DOCNO> APW20000928.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Soarss 203; Nasdaq Rises 98  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks shot higher Thursday, buoyed by rebounds
in technology and blue chip issues, as the market apparently
regained its footing despite worries about corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, the first consistent advance this week, came as
bargain hunters pushed stocks higher across the board. The gains
were especially strong in the technology sector, which has been
battered for most of the month.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 202.73 at 10,831.03, its highest level
this week. The Dow fell in each of the first three sessions this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 31.28 at 1,457.85, and the Nasdaq composite index
rose 97.74 to 3,754.04.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Nie, a technical analyst at First Union Securities, didn't
see any one driving force behind the market's behavior. He said of
the Dow, ''you simply have 23 issues up and only seven down, and
that's better news.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have been down for most of September on worries about
corporate profits. And investors have punished stocks of companies
that even hint at disappointing results when third-quarter results
are announced next month.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the stress are energy prices at decade-high levels
and a weak European currency -- factors that many companies say will
hurt their profits.
</P>
<P>
   A Commerce Department report released Thursday raised new
questions about whether the Federal Reserve's efforts to slow
growth to a more sustainable level have worked.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, which showed the economy expanding at a rate of
5.6 percent between April and June, a faster rate than the 4.8
percent growth in the first three months of 2000, didn't seem to
cause much concern on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the market rallied on a mix of bargain-hunting and
end-of-the-month trading.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again focused on corporate earnings, although their
reactions weren't consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble jumped $5.19 to $67.06 after the consumer
products manufacturer said it would meet Wall Street expectations
for the third quarter after several disappointing quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But profit-taking investors unloaded Safeway, trading it down
$4.31 to $49.81, although the grocery store chain reported profits
in line with analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Investor enthusiasm also appeared to be behind a mild recovery
by Internet and telecom stocks, which have been in a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which makes telecom equipment, was up $1.81 at
$59.13, despite a downgrade by a Sanford Bernstein analyst.
Competitor Nortel Networks rose $4.28 to $63.56, halting a decline
that began the previous session. Lucent also moved higher, trading
up $3.25 at $31.81.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed Hewlett Packard up $3.94 to $106.75.
</P>
<P>
   And Web portal Yahoo! was up $5.56 at $95.94, gaining back
nearly half of its loss Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're getting some good boost of stocks that have been
bludgeoned as of late,'' said Charles White, portfolio manager at
Avatar Associates. ''You may have a little bit of bargain hunting
going on ... and a little bit of relief that we've gone one day
maybe without a company announcing a complete disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   News of a $6.5 billion merger between Global Crossing and
Exodus, two Web site hosting companies, got a mixed reactions.
Exodus fell $3.19 to $50.06. Global Crossing was up $2.06 at
$31.94.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 15-to-8 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 932.46 million
shares, ahead of the 925.16 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 11.25 at 519.38.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
