<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congressman wages ''Save the District'' campaign  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CORNING, N.Y. (AP) - Amo Houghton, looking for an eighth term in
Congress, has been running a second campaign on the side: one to
save his district from being eliminated or rearranged.
</P>
<P>
   With the lagging population likely to cost New York two seats in
Congress in 2002, the Republican has started a petition drive that
aims to send 100,000 signatures to the state Legislature. The
message: when the lines are redrawn, the Southern Tier district
should remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Houghton is raising $250,000 to help preserve the
state Senate's Republican majority - a key factor, he says, in
preserving his district.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be very easy to chop this district up,'' Houghton
said. ''Maybe the Legislature will end up saying that's the way
it's going to be, but if so, we're going to go down with all guns
firing.''
</P>
<P>
   Houghton, whose 31st Congressional District touches 10 counties
from Lake Erie in Chautauqua County to the Finger Lakes, fears
important issues, such as the conversion of Route 17 into
interstate highway I-86, would get lost if his district were
parceled off to congressmen from upstate's big cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people in Fredonia think the way people in Ithaca do, and
the people in Jamestown think the way the people in Elmira do - not
the way people in Buffalo and Rochester think,'' Houghton told The
Buffalo News. ''There's a way of life here, and we want to preserve
it and expand the opportunities. But if they divide this district
up, it takes away everything we're trying to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   Census estimates show Houghton's district has lost about 20,000
residents in 10 years and other upstate districts have lost similar
numbers. Such districts are at greatest risk in reapportionment,
though Houghton's is the one frequently mentioned as endangered.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, some Buffalo-area political players are not
opposed to putting pieces of Houghton's district in one based in
Erie County.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the issues of southern Erie County are very similar to
those in Chautauqua and Cattaraugus counties,'' said Erie County
Republican Chairman Robert Davis. ''Putting them together would not
be a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   To preserve his district, Houghton recently established the
Millennium Project, a state political action committee that already
has contributions and pledges totaling $250,000 to help state
Senate Republican candidates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton said a Republican Senate is key to his district's
survival, believing Democrats would surely favor urban interests in
the reapportionment process.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and Assembly will share in redrawing the
congressional lines with Gov. George Pataki. Work will begin after
the Census Bureau announces the number of seats for each state in
late December.
</P>
<P>
   By helping Republican Senate candidates, Houghton is expanding
on former Rep. Bill Paxon's 1990 pledge of $100,000. Critics
accused Paxon then - and Houghton now - of trying to buy a safe
Republican seat.
</P>
<P>
   ''This just goes to show how partisan the reapportionment
process is, and we actually think that's indefensible,'' said Blair
Horner of the New York Public Interest Research Group
</P>
<P>
   Houghton said his motives are much different from those of
Paxon, who was a young congressman trying to preserve his political
future. Houghton, the millionaire scion of the family that founded
Corning Inc., stresses he's trying to save the district rather than
his job.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Paxon, Houghton also has enlisted Democrats in the
cause. Business owners and students have also been out collecting
signatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1547 </TRAILER>
