<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials to go door-to-door to test for West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The city is taking its campaign against the West
Nile virus door-to-door in Staten Island in an attempt to determine
how many people have been infected by the potentially deadly
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island has been the epicenter of the city's battle
against West Nile this year, with nine of the 13 human cases and
the majority of infected birds coming from that borough.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when northern Queens was hard hit by the virus, a
similar survey was conducted by city and federal health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most human infections have occurred on Staten Island and by
focusing on this borough, we hope to get a better understanding of
West Nile virus and its risk factors for infection,'' health
department commissioner Neal Cohen said in a statement Thursday.
''The understanding will further improve the effectiveness of
mosquito-borne disease prevention and control strategies for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   During the survey, which will begin Oct. 3, health officials
will go door-to-door collecting blood samples from residents.
Participation is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   The results will likely take several months to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   During last year's testing in Queens, anonymous donors gave
blood at vans parked throughout the neighborhoods, possibly skewing
the test results since it could not be determined if all of those
tested actually lived in those neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   By going door-to-door in Staten Island, health officials hope to
get a more accurate snapshot of how many may have contracted the
mosquito-borne disease.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, officials announced an 82-year-old New Jersey man
was the first confirmed death from West Nile this year.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which has flu-like symptoms and can be dangerous to
young children, the elderly and people with weakened immune
systems, has been detected in birds in Maryland, New Jersey,
Connecticut, Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The virus first appearance in the New York metropolitan region
last summer, killing seven and infecting 55 others. It was the
first time it had ever appeared in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
