<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soggy summer could mean a colorful fall in New England  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - New England's summer was a bummer - rainy
and cool. But the silver lining to the lowering clouds may be an
unusually bright fall foliage season.
</P>
<P>
   The wet weather and low temperatures reduced stress on the
region's maples, oaks and birches, and healthy, vigorous trees are
colorful trees, said David Kittredge of the Department of Natural
Resources Conservation at the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Leaves are covered with small holes called stomates that allow
them to exchange carbon dioxide and oxygen through photosynthesis,
Kittredge explained.
</P>
<P>
   During a dry summer, Kittredge said, the leaves close their
holes to avoid losing moisture. Photosynthesis is slowed down, the
trees don't grow as well and produce fewer, less-vibrant leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ''The critical factor is a moisture thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a drought affected the ''leaf-peeping'' season. This
year, Donald Smith, Connecticut's state forester, expects leaves
that are bigger, healthier and more plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Although the northeastern and northwestern corners of
Connecticut are often touted for their trees, Smith said this year
''everything's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the state should be pretty wonderful viewing,'' he
said. ''This is one of the better years we've seen in the past 10
or 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has predicted that the foliage will peak between Oct.
12-15, but admits ''it really is a gamble when you start telling
people particular dates.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Stone, the chief of forestry management for the Vermont
Department of Forests and Parks, agreed. Exactly when the trees
will change each year and what their colors will be like is largely
a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ''All this prediction stuff is BS,'' Stone said. ''No one knows
what it will be like, but it's going to be beautiful. I've lived in
the north country for 59 years and I've never seen a bad foliage
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The soggy summer also means the foliage season is more important
financially for innkeepers, tour guides and other tourism
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Individual and group tour reservations are already ahead of
where they were at this time last year, said Ed Dombroskas,
executive director of the Connecticut Office of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated $1.27 billion and some 4 million anticipated
visitors on the line, Diane Konrady, a spokeswoman for the Vermont
Department of Tourism and Marketing, said: ''It's still a little
early, but what we're seeing in some of the northern areas is very
promising.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, some 28 million people drive 50 miles or more
from home to visit state tourism sites during autumn, said Fritz
Smith, a spokesman for the state's Center for Travel and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ''The emphasis on leisure travel used to be solely on the
summer, but we've seen it shift more to fall,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Although average gas prices in New England ranged Tuesday from a
high of $1.72 in Connecticut to a low of $1.58 in Vermont, a
spokeswoman for the AAA in Hartford said the cost of fuel shouldn't
be a ''trip breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If Labor Day is any indication, it should be a good fall
season,'' spokeswoman Kelly Carter said. Despite high gasoline
prices, the summer travel season ''really wound down with a bang,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nelson Houston, pastor at the White Mountain Chapel in
Conway, N.H., said the fall colors bring out faithful leaf peepers
as well as the plain old faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at the chapel increases as much as 10 percent during
prime foliage season. But Houston said he doesn't change his
sermons to cater to the leaf-loving crowd.
</P>
<P>
   God is God, after all, and probably doesn't care that people
plan to gawk at trees following the service.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had them come all the way from California and England,''
he said. ''I thought flying from England to see leaves was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans of fall foliage find the region's natural beauty runs
deeper than the annual turning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to explain,'' said Bruce Byberg, owner of Brighter
Skies Balloon Co. in Woodstock, Conn., which offers foliage flights
to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole experience of going up in the balloon, how quiet it
is ... the color of the leaves is lower on their list than when
they started the ride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1607 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000928.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tensions Mount in Ivory Coast  </HEADLINE>
By AMBA DADSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Fist-pumping young protesters turned
out by the hundreds Thursday in an angry show of support for Ivory
Coast's junta leader, denouncing international pressure on him
ahead of upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   The rally signaled growing resistance by Gen. Robert Guei's
regime to outside calls that he let the country's opposition leader
run against him in an Oct. 22 presidential vote. The vote has been
called to return Ivory Coast to civilian control after nine months
of military rule.
</P>
<P>
   The rally -- held despite the junta's own ban on political
gatherings -- came three days after some of Africa's most
influential heads of state intervened to try to resolve Ivory
Coast's tense political situation. The African leaders, under the
auspices of the Organization of African Unity, urged Guei to open
the vote to opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Guei reaffirmed his earlier rejection of the
proposals, telling the demonstrators that Ivorians were capable of
handling their own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are responsible enough. Our will is what has already been
translated into the constitution,'' Guei said to cheers and
applause.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500-strong crowd, mostly young men, turned upon
journalists working for foreign organizations, forcing several to
flee under security forces' escort.
</P>
<P>
   ''Foreigners out!'' the Guei supporters shouted, some waving
posters denouncing the Organization of African Unity for its
pressure for fair and open elections.
</P>
<P>
   Ivory Coast's foremost opposition leader, Alassane Dramane
Ouattara, is a northerner in a political arena long dominated by
southerners.
</P>
<P>
   Guei's supporters claim one of Ouattara's parents is
foreign-born, which would disqualify him for the race under a
junta-backed constitution voted in last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara, a former premier and ex-International Monetary Fund
official, insists both his parents were Ivorian-born.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara's supporters have surrounded his house day and night
for more than a week, fearing a move against him by the junta.
</P>
<P>
   Guei came to power after a Christmas Eve military coup, the
first in the history of the 40-year-old nation. The coup, and two
smaller military uprisings since, have shaken the country's
standing as a valued center of stability in troubled West Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 1608 </TRAILER>
