<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Day Rail Strike Stalls France  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French transport workers staged a one-day strike
Thursday that brought almost all the country's trains to a halt and
snarled highway traffic for miles outside the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Public transportation within Paris was not affected by the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Morning traffic around Paris was backed up for miles, and
evening traffic also was stalled, the National Center for Road
Information said. Bad weather aggravated the strike.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of France's 15 rail worker unions took part in the
strike to seek higher pay, better retirement packages, more jobs
and progress on putting the mandatory 35-hour work week into
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very important day and it shows the determination of
rail workers to get results on salaries and use all necessary
force,'' said Jean-Michel Sgorlol, an official at the CGT trade
union. ''We said at the beginning of September that if things did
not change, there would be action. Now we want real negotiations
with real propositions,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Talks on salaries are to start Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The national rail authority advised passengers to find
alternative means of transportation, as only 30 percent of trains
were operating. Rail service between major French cities, such as
Paris and Marseille, was also disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, which began Wednesday evening, was to end Friday
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
