<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vague on Political Future  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
returned home from the United States Thursday, a day after a
corruption case against him was closed, but he was vague about a
political comeback.
</P>
<P>
   While supporters urged him to challenge Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, who trounced him in an election in May 1999, Netanyahu put
off questions about his future.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in front of his father's house in a quiet
Jerusalem neighborhood, Netanyahu indicated that if he re-enters
politics, he will adopt a conciliatory tone. ''To the extent it
depends on me,'' said Netanyahu, political discussions ''will
always be done with mutual respect.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was prime minister from 1996 to 1999, Netanyahu's
opponents vilified him as a divisive leader who incited segments of
the society against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lesson I learned'' over the past year, he said, is that
''we are all brothers living in the same country, that we have the
same future.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu looked relaxed and fit as he gave a statement to
reporters, but refused to answer questions. He had been in the
United States working as an adviser to start-up companies and
keeping largely out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   As premier, Netanyahu opposed concessions to the Palestinians,
but under heavy American pressure, he signed two interim peace
agreements. Barak was elected on a moderate platform that included
trading West Bank territory for peace.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein rejected a
police recommendation to put Netanyahu on trial for allegedly
conspiring with a government contractor in a kickback scheme,
illegally keeping gifts and obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein ruled that there was insufficient evidence to assure
a conviction, but he sharply criticized Netanyahu's behavior in
office, saying that it ''had an element of ugliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu expressed relief over Rubinstein's ruling, which would
clear the way for him to return to politics. It comes at a time
when Barak is vulnerable to a challenge. Though he trounced
Netanyahu by 56 percent to 44, Barak has been losing ground ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that Barak and Netanyahu are running
even, though significant numbers of voters say they are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament elected along with Barak is more favorable to his
hard-line predecessor, Netanyahu. Barak built a coalition dominated
by Netanyahu's ex-partners, all of whom deserted him as he prepared
to offer concessions to the Palestinians for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu maintained throughout that the police investigation,
which included long hours of interrogation, leaks to the local news
media and searches of his home and belongings, was politically
motivated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
