<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 196; Nasdaq Adds 105  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks shot higher Thursday, buoyed by rebounds
in technology and blue chip issues as the market apparently
regained its footing amid uncertainty about corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The upturn was a dramatic comeback for a market that has taken a
beating all week on concerns about third-quarter earnings, higher
oil prices and the weak European currency.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 195.70 at 10,824.06,
according to preliminary calculations, its highest close this week.
The Dow fell in each of the previous three sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 29.04 at 1,455.61, and the Nasdaq composite index
rose 105.19 to 3,3761.49.
</P>
<P>
   The market advanced on a mix of bargain-hunting and
end-of-the-quarter trading.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a pretty broad-based rally. I'm look at technology,
banking, and several other sectors all up,'' said Dan Ascani,
president and research director at Global Market Strategists in
Gainesville, Ga. ''You've got a situation where you've had a lot of
earnings warnings and a washout in some stocks, so some of these
stocks are going to picked up at real bargains,''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have been down for most of September on worries about
corporate profits. And investors have punished stocks of companies
that even hint at disappointing results when third-quarter results
are announced next month.
</P>
<P>
   The market's unease has been compounded by energy prices that
are at decade-high levels and a weak European currency -- factors
that many companies say will hurt their profits.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared unfazed by a Commerce Department report
Thursday that showed the economy expanded at an annual rate of 5.6
percent between April and June, a faster rate than the 4.8 percent
growth in the first three months of 2000. The report also showed
inflation, which has been the primary concern of the Federal
Reserve as it raised interest rates over the past 15 months, was
moderating even as the economy surged.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again focused on corporate earnings. Procter &AMP; Gamble
jumped $5.13 to $67 after the consumer products maker said it would
meet Wall Street expectations for the third quarter after several
disappointing quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But profit-taking investors unloaded Safeway, trading it down
$3.75 to $50.38 after the grocery company reported profits in line
with analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Internet and telecom stocks also emerged from a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems was up $2 at $59.31, despite a downgrade by a
Sanford Bernstein analyst. Nortel Networks rose $4.09 to $63.38,
halting a decline that began the previous session. Lucent also
moved higher, trading up $2.75 at $31.31.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed Hewlett Packard up $4.06 to $106.88.
</P>
<P>
   And Web portal Yahoo! was up $5.31 at $95.69, gaining back
nearly half of its loss Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're getting some good boost of stocks that have been
bludgeoned as of late,'' said Charles White, portfolio manager at
Avatar Associates. ''You may have a little bit of bargain hunting
going on ... and a little bit of relief that we've gone one day
maybe without a company announcing a complete disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial services stocks moved higher as well. Citigroup
climbed $1.50 to $53.88 and J.P. Morgan was up $5.25 at $166.44.
Dain Rauscher, a regional brokerage firm, rose $13 to $92.88 after
announcing it was being acquired by the Royal Bank of Canada in a
$1.5 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a more than 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.19
billion shares, ahead of the 1.16 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 13.20 at 521.33.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.08 percent.
Germany's DAX index was up .27 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 dropped
0.08 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
