<HEADLINE> Students Ask For Help To End Slavery  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Five children sat patiently Thursday as their
teacher wept in a Senate hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters had asked the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
to help them in their 3-year-old campaign to end slavery in Sudan
and around the world. And teacher Barbara Vogel cried at the
thought that the senators would not.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado sixth-grader Dong Cho spoke first.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to do homework, chores, and go to school -- and I still
have time to help,'' said Cho, who has raised money to buy back
slaves. ''Is Congress too busy?''
</P>
<P>
   But a more disheartened Vogel noted that only two of 18 senators
on the committee had come to the hearing. And she charged the
government had largely remained ''deaf'' to their campaign and to
the plight of the enslaved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senators, please support these students. If you do not,'' she
said choking back tears, ''what can I possibly teach them?
</P>
<P>
   ''Can I still teach them that our government stands for right
... our country stands for principles ... that we are the home of
the brave?''
</P>
<P>
   The group came from Highland School in Aurora, Colo., where
Vogel founded S.T.O.P.(Slavery that Oppresses People). It has
raised money to buy back hundreds of slaves in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Along with freed slaves from Haiti, Mauritania and Sudan, they
spoke at a hearing that the committee chairman, Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., said was to draw attention to the ''vicious inhumanity'' of
slavery, ''particularly in the Sudan.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis Bok, a southern Sudanese of the Dinka tribe, said he was
captured by Arab militia in Sudan at the age of 7 and enslaved to
work for an Arab family for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today in Sudan and around the world, there are children who
cannot sleep at night -- they lie on the ground and they wait for
strong people to come and free them,'' he said. ''Senators, you are
strong people. ... You can free the slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudan denies its army has enslaved captives taken during the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department this year for the first time included data
on trafficking of human beings in its annual human rights report to
try to highlight the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has not implemented a recommendation from a
national commission on religous freedom, which suggested tougher
sanctions and other pressure on Sudan for alleged atrocities in the
Arab government's 17-year war against the country's animist and
Christian southerners.
</P>
</TEXT>
