<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Buildings Department employees, three others indicted  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Five high-ranking employees of the Department of
Buildings and three other people have been indicted on charges of
accepting bribes or gratuities to influence the performance of
their duties.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, including the department's second
highest-ranking official, allegedly took cash, meals, wine,
vacation trips, and tickets to sports and theater events in
exchange for favors that included expedited or invalid approvals of
construction permits and plans.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors would not say who gave the city officials the bribes
and gifts, but Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said
many of them have pleaded guilty and are cooperating with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The probe was conducted by Morgenthau's office and the
Department of Investigations. Edward Kuriansky, DOI's commissioner,
called the buildings department ''the most corruption-prone agency
in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This case represents the fourth major corruption scandal in
the New York City Buildings Department in the past decade alone,''
Kuriansky said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This two-year joint investigation has yielded disturbing
evidence of a pervasive culture of corruption within and without
the department and extends to licensed professionals and the
commissioner level,'' Kuriansky said.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-ranking defendant is Barry Cox, DOB's deputy
commissioner for operations and the agency's second highest-ranking
officer. He is accused of violating the law that requires him to
disclose certain gifts he receives.
</P>
<P>
   High-ranking city officials are required to tell DOI about all
gifts worth more than $50 that they receive from people who do
business with the city. They also must tell the city's Conflict of
Interest Board about any gift they receive that is valued at more
than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The six-count indictment charged Cox, 52, of Nutley, N.J., with
two felony counts of filing a false instrument and four misdemeanor
counts of receiving unlawful gratuities.
</P>
<P>
   Cox allegedly failed to report receipt of a family trip to
Florida, tickets to hockey games, and wine. It is not alleged that
he did anything in exchange for the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky said the Buildings Department has been the agency most
''stubbornly resistant'' to reform, and ''utterly undeterred by
repeated arrests, prosecutions and disciplinary proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Over 100 building inspectors (out of 250) have been arrested
in the past two years,'' Kuriansky said. ''Many others have been
disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Buildings Department has to be completely
overhauled,'' Kuriansky said. He said the answer might be to have a
shake-up and put in ''a real manager'' and maybe remove some of the
agency's responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The other four DOB employees are:
</P>
<P>
   James Leonard, 40, Belle Harbor, N.Y., the Queens Borough
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mineo, 58, Danbury, Conn., DOB's executive chief
inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Darral Hilton, 46, Queens, administrative chief inspector for
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Siegfried Wyner, 44, Rego Park, Queens; a DOB plans examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The other three indicted defendants are:
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Cunningham, 54, Long Beach, N.Y., retired chief of the
Bureau of Fire Prevention of the New York City Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Yagasits, 49, Yonkers, N.Y., former Department of
Transportation employee.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Defronzo, 51, Voorheesville, N.Y., employee of the state
Canal Authority, which is a subsidiary of the state Thruway
Authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1708 </TRAILER>
