<DOCNO> APW20000928.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador issues harsh warning on genocide resolution  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The U.S. ambassador to Turkey warned lawmakers
Thursday that approving a resolution recognizing the killing of
Armenians in Turkey as a genocide could cause significant harm to
relations with a key military ally.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is a NATO member and the United States uses the Incirlik
air base in southern Turkey to patrol the no-fly zone in northern
Iraq. There is concern that passage of the resolution could
endanger American use of the base.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a strong Turkish reaction,'' Ambassador Robert
Pearson told the House International Relations Committee. '' ...
This is designed to make Turkish-American relations and the issues
we are trying to deal with more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution before the Committee on International Relations
is nonbinding but would place the U.S. government on record as
confirming that 1.5 million Armenians were killed or displaced
between 1915 and 1923 at the hands of the Ottoman Empire
government.
</P>
<P>
   The committee postponed a vote until next week.
</P>
<P>
   Armenians maintain their people were slaughtered as part of an
Ottoman campaign to force Armenians out of eastern Turkey. The
Turks deny they ever engaged in genocide. They acknowledge some
300,000 Armenians were killed, but say the deaths occurred as the
Ottoman Empire tried to quell civil unrest. The Ottoman Empire
became Turkey in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, it's a battle between New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Reps. Gerald Solomon, a Republican, and Steve
Solarz, Democrat, are being paid $1.1 million to lobby for the
Turkish government against the genocide resolution. And former Rep.
Susan Molinari signed on this week to work for pro-Armenian
activists.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, whose firm is being paid $700,000, said it is wrong for
the American government to insult Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we were getting our butts shot off in Korea the Turks
were right there on the front lines with us,'' Solomon said. ''They
have been one of our strongest allies.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said the killing of Armenians needed to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Silence in the face of genocide, as we have learned, can only
embolden those who would again seek the systematic destruction of
an entire people,'' said Rep. George Radanovich, R-Calif. and the
resolution's prime sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Radanovich dropped one controversial portion of the resolution
that would have mandated the Clinton administration provide
training on the Armenian deaths for executive branch employees.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem described the
committee hearing as a ''tasteless development.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Turkey is a strong country, a strong society and we will do
anything we can do to make sure that a wrong decision will not be
taken in a foreign parliament,'' Cem said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration opposes the resolution. U.S. defense
contractors, who either have deals or are negotiating deals with
Turkey, have been lobbying heavily against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers on the committee expressed reservations about
angering such a powerful ally for actions that occurred long ago by
a government no longer in power. Others pointed out that other
atrocities, such as slavery and the mistreatment of American
Indians, have not been the subject of critical resolutions in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the critics was Rep. Tom Lantos, the only
Holocaust survivor in Congress. Lantos, D-Calif., said the
consequences of deliberately insulting a NATO ally could be
''devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   He proposed a more sweeping resolution that would recognize
human rights crimes of the 20th century. It would include the
killings of Armenians but would not single out Turkey as the
perpetrator. That was rejected by committee Chairman Benjamin
Gilman, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers said Congress has a moral obligation to do
something.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is genocide denial in Turkey. That is what this is all
about,'' Rep. Edward Royce, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution is H.R. 596.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.armenian-genocide.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.turkey.org/intro.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
