<HEADLINE> Wife of Prisoner Pleads With Russia  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The tearful wife of an American businessman
imprisoned in Moscow on spying charges on Thursday pleaded for the
Russian government to allow her husband to be tested to see if his
cancer has returned.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a lot of faith that we are going to get him home
eventually but realistically he needs a doctor now, or yesterday.
He needs medical testing. My fear ratio is sky high,'' said Cheryl
Pope of her husband Edmond, who has been imprisoned since April.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had not spoken to her husband since she visited him
in August but fears for his health because the Russians have denied
him medical treatment. She said she wants the Russian government to
give her husband access to advanced X-ray equipment so physicians
can determine if his bone cancer, which is in remission, has
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Edmond Pope, 54, has been held in Moscow's Lefortovo prison
since April 5, when Russia's Federal Security Service arrested him
and said he had illegally bought plans for a high-speed torpedo. On
Wednesday, Russian prosecutors said they have officially charged
him with spying, clearing the way for a trial expected to begin
next month. Pope, who lives in State College, Pa., faces 20 years
in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pope said her husband looked ''terrible'' when she saw
him on CNN earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was pale and had lost weight and looked like he did when he
originally had the bone cancer, that is why I am concerned,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Peterson, R-Pa., who represents Pope's district, wrote
President Clinton on Thursday urging Clinton to encourage Russian
President Vladimir Putin to give Pope access to medical care.
Peterson said Marconi PLC, a London-based high technology firm
which has a manufacturing plant in Pennsylvania, has offered to pay
for the medical tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Embassy in Washington did not return phone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering met with Peterson and
Cheryl Pope on Thursday and said the administration was working
hard to free Edmund Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said Pickering told them that the administration is
''developing a game plan to keep the pressure on Russia.'
</P>
<P>
   Peterson has introduced a nonbinding resolution urging the
Clinton administration to cut all aid to Russia if Pope is not
released. The House International Relations Committee had been
scheduled to discuss the measure on Thursday but postponed it until
next week because it did not complete other business.
</P>
<P>
   Pope, a retired naval intelligence officer, runs CERF
Technologies International, a consulting firm in State College,
Pa., that developed commercial contacts with Russian organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
