<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Play Proves Everyone Has a Story  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Only 15 minutes of fame? Not at off-Broadway's
Jane Street Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The ''onstage guests'' in ''Lifegame'' get nearly two hours'
worth of celebrity, proving that sometimes theater has it all over
real life.
</P>
<P>
   That's because everyone has a story to tell, or so say members
of the Improbable Theatre, a British troupe that improvises on its
guests' lives with surprising, often very funny results. The trick
is in the telling, which these ingratiating performers do with
zest, wit and even compassion for their source material.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lifegame'' is a genial show, not mean-spirited or competitive
like those so-called reality shows on television, ''Survivor'' and
''Big Brother.'' It isn't judgmental about its subject's
peculiarities. In fact, ''Lifegame'' revels in them.
</P>
<P>
   The subjects -- who are not members of the audience -- are
preselected and are willing participants in these theatrical
biographies. Most have found their way to ''Lifegame'' through
advertisements for the show, word-of-mouth or through its Web site
(http://www.lifegamenyc.com).
</P>
<P>
   On the night caught by this critic, the star was a Brooklyn
housewife named Nancy Rosenthal, who described herself as ''a
stay-at-home mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal was ''interviewed'' by Lee Simpson, the Improbable's
co-artistic director. Simpson, a cross between David Frost and
Barbara Walters (but with less hair), dug skillfully into his
subject's life. He displayed a deftness that made the questioning
sound casual, even though it was part psychiatric probing and part
gossipy intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal selected performer Angela Clerkin to play her. The
others -- Stella Duffy, Niall Ashdown, Phelim McDermott and musician
Toby Park -- sat on the sidelines and listened closely as Rosenthal
spun her story. They portrayed the other characters in her life.
</P>
<P>
   Good improvisation needs structure, a framework in which the
performers can be as freewheeling as possible. Simpson provided
that framework. He took his subject down an obvious chronological
path -- childhood, grade school, relationship with best friend,
first date and, in the show's second half, meeting, bedding and
then wedding her future husband.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal talked of dinner times with her dysfunctional family:
a loud, overbearing father; an acquiescent, yet glamorous mother; a
combative older brother. Immediately, several chairs and a table
were produced, and the actors acted out what happened during a
meal. Ashdown gloriously personified the macho head of the
household, fine-tuning his obscenity-laced bellowing after
suggestions from Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's show-stopping moments were provided by the subject
herself. One occurred in the first act, when Rosenthal was
encouraged to reminisce about two nuns who taught her in grade
school. Some lessons are not forgotten -- particularly one that
Rosenthal repeated to wild applause. In a hilarious parochial
school memory, she sang a laundry list of prepositions -- above,
around, about, in, out, etc. -- that turned into the grammatical
equivalent of ''Rose's Turn'' from ''Gypsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the evening was over, Rosenthal revealed her dream job
would be a talk show host. Of course, it's the perfect profession
for her. The woman has remarkable poise. She held her own with the
professional performers, even when she joined them in an imaginary
talk show centered on her.
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of risk in ''Lifegame.'' Who knows if
another ''guest'' will be as right-on as Nancy Rosenthal? Still,
you are advised to take a chance on ''Lifegame.'' Ordinary folk
have never seemed like so much fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 1721 </TRAILER>
