<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hoboken, Oakland developments deemed state's best, worst  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A New Jersey environmental group has
weighed in on the state's best and worst development projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Metuchen Square development in Hoboken combines all the best
elements of planning - mixed housing and retail uses, green spaces,
and access to public transportation, according to the New Jersey
Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramapo River Reserve development in Oakland, Bergen County,
on the other hand, damaged area mountains, pollutes local water
supply and opens up a previously pristine environment to more
sprawl, according to the club.
</P>
<P>
   The club reviewed more than 50 development projects in the state
before narrowing the list for inclusion in the ''Smart Choices or
Sprawling Growth'' 50-state survey.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Tittel, director of the New Jersey Sierra Club, said the
report is aimed at raising awareness about and ultimately stemming
suburban sprawl. It is also designed to applaud developers who do
it right, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, New Jersey is seeing its largest building boom in a
generation,'' he said. ''We're losing 50,000 acres of year to
development and that's having consequences on water quality ... and
air quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra staffers used about 30 criteria to judge which were the
best and worst among the state's largest developments.
</P>
<P>
   The 450-unit Oakland development topped the worst offenders,
according to Tittel.
</P>
<P>
   ''In exchange for a few luxury homes in an isolated and
car-dependent community, the developers destroyed greenways, turned
trout streams into steel pipes, carved away parts of the Ramapo
Mountains and caused other severe environmental damage,'' according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
   But the president of the development company that built Ramapo
River Reserve disputed the Sierra Club's characterization.
</P>
<P>
   Baker Residential president Marc Baker said the report failed to
note that the 400 houses are clustered to preserve 200 contiguous
acres of the total 300-acre parcel as open space, and that builders
abided by state environmental regulations to protect the Ramapo
River.
</P>
<P>
   ''They say we've been hostile to wildlife, and we erected 300
birdhouses on the property,'' he said. ''We have tried to be as
friendly to the environment as we can because environmentally
friendly features add value to a project.''
</P>
<P>
   No one from the Hoboken project could be reached for comment by
The Associated Press on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tittel said Metuchen Square is a model of how to redevelop an
urban, waterfront parcel to make it attractive enough to entice
residents and businesses away from open space-destroying
subdivisions or office parks in the suburbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1722 </TRAILER>
