<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brooklyn judge agrees to release mob turncoat  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Brooklyn kid started out the old-school way,
shining shoes in a mob social club.
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, he soon began stealing to please wiseguys.
Then running card games. Then killing, and killing again.
</P>
<P>
   ''The movie ''Goodfellas'' explains it well,'' recalled mob
turncoat Carmine Sessa. ''Everybody gets killed by a bunch of
animals or so-called 'friends.' ... This thing I thought I
respected as a young man has no respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessa offered his somber insights in Brooklyn federal court
Thursday before a judge released him from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the families hate each other, and within the families they
hate one another,'' said Sessa, who rose to consigliere, or
third-in-command, of the Colombo organized crime family at a time
the family was torn by a bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Sessa, 49, pleaded guilty in 1993 to being part of a murderous
Bensonhurst-based crew which operated out of the Wimpy Boys Social
Club. He admitted he was the triggerman in the slayings of three
men and one woman in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to avoid a life sentence, Sessa also became one of the
highest ranking cooperators in the government's war on La Cosa
Nostra. At his long-delayed sentencing Thursday, prosecutors said
he deserved credit for having the courage to testify against
reputed members of the Colombo and Genovese families in eight
federal trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''His cooperation was extraordinary,'' prosecutor George
Stamboulidis told U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein agreed, sentencing Sessa to time served - he has spent
much of the past seven years in federal custody - and five years
probation. He is expected to go free in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was sentenced, Sessa apologized to his ''victims and
their families, who still suffer their loss every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The mobster claimed that he now looks back on his career with
shame and sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wound up growing up and around a life that was and is a
disease,'' he said, reading from a handwritten statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate everything about the life I led, and I hope that it
ends soon, because it keeps destroying families and kids who are
infatuated with it and can't wait to be 'goodfellas''' he added.
''I wish I could tell them what it really is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
