<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cop-killer resentenced to life in prison  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DANIELSON, Conn. (AP) - Terry Johnson, convicted in the 1991
fatal shooting of a state trooper, was re-sentenced Thursday to
life in prison without chance of parole.
</P>
<P>
   The re-sentencing comes five months after the state Supreme
Court overturned Johnson's death sentence, ruling the state didn't
prove Johnson inflicted extreme physical pain or mental torture
when he fired upon Trooper Russell Bagshaw outside a North Windham
gun shop in June, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bagshaw was shot and killed while on routine patrol when he
interrupted an early morning burglary.
</P>
<P>
   The trial jury ruled that Johnson should be executed because
Bagshaw, 28, of Columbia, had been terrorized when he was ambushed.
The high court said Bagshaw died only a few seconds after being
shot and that there was no evidence Johnson tried to prolong his
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Windham States Attorney Mark Solak, who had originally obtained
the death penalty for Johnson, said the court decision should drive
the state Legislature to change the law so that killing a police
officer automatically results in the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the increase in violence that police officers have
suffered, the law needs to be changed to protect the officers,''
Solak said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagshaw's widow, Carol spoke at the sentencing hearing, calling
Johnson a coward.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way you killed Russell was as cowardly as killing a
2-year-old in a sandbox,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also called the Supreme Court's decision to overturn
Johnson's death sentence ''cowardly,'' but called on Johnson not to
waste his time in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask you to make the best of your second chance at life,and
be the person who would make his father proud,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1756 </TRAILER>
