<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health care workers' union officials convicted of embezzling funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A federal jury convicted the president of a
health care workers' union and his son Thursday of conspiring to
take $200,000 from the union's pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated 12 hours over three days before returning a
verdict against Victor Garcia, 62, of New Hope, Pa., and his son
Victor Garcia Jr., 37, of Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Garcia is former president of District 1199J, part of
the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees,
which represents about 10,000 health care workers in state nursing
homes and hospitals. Garcia Jr. was the union pension fund's
assistant executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The men were convicted of taking the $200,000 in kickbacks from
a contractor who performed $6 million of renovations at the pension
fund's Newark building between 1994-1997. The contractor also paid
for the repair of the elder Garcia's car, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Garcia faces up to 11 years in prison and $750,000 in
fines for his convictions on charges of conspiracy and soliciting
and receiving kickbacks. The younger Garcia faces up to five years
in prison and a $250,000 fine for a conspiracy conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gluck, the attorney for Garcia Jr., said Thursday he may
appeal on issues that include the court's denial of holding two
separate trials for the men. He said jurors may have considered
Garcia Jr., who was acquitted on three other counts, guilty because
of his relationship to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ''The jury must have found that somehow he facilitated his
father taking money,'' Gluck said conviction.
</P>
<P>
   George Schneider, the elder Garcia's attorney, did not return a
message seeking comment Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
