<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans say first lady's travel records contain errors  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - A House Republican charged Thursday that the
White House had provided his committee with erroneous information
on Hillary Rodham Clinton's travel on government aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Kolbe, R-Ariz., said a new report he received from
the White House late Wednesday contained 28 changes to flight
hours, five revisions to destinations and showed earlier expense
reports had failed to account for seven trips.
</P>
<P>
   Lissa Muscatine, a spokeswoman for the first lady, chalked up
the discrepancies to clerical errors ''which inevitably resulted
from trying to assemble a huge amount of data in an unreasonably
short time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We reimbursed precisely as the law requires and if they don't
like the law they ought to change it,'' Muscatine said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kolbe, whose committee oversees White House spending, said
he has lost confidence that the information he is receiving is
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The White House is providing my committee with incomplete,
inaccurate and sloppy data,'' Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At best this is an example of bureaucratic incompetence. At
worst it's an attempt to cover up the true cost to taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flies on government aircraft on the request of the
Secret Service. She reimburses the government the same way
presidential candidates do: at the rate of a first-class commercial
ticket. That is well below the actual cost of her travel.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is legal but has been criticized by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe estimates that the first lady's campaign travel during the
U.S. Senate race has cost taxpayers just over $1 million so far.
She has reimbursed a total of $203,700.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe's committee held a hearing on the travel arrangements in
March and directed the White House to provide monthly expense
reports.
</P>
<P>
   He requested additional information earlier this month after
news reports noted that state Assemblyman Michael Bragman and his
family had traveled on the first lady's plane from Syracuse to
Washington Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier data provided to Kolbe did not include the Syracuse
stop and listed only one political passenger on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The new report includes Syracuse in the itinerary and now
includes seven political passengers on the trip. The campaign must
reimburse taxpayers for political passengers on board the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The new information also showed that Clinton is not only flying
on C-20s, but on at least one occasion flew on a C-32, a larger
aircraft which is comparable in size to a commercial 757. On that
Nov. 4 trip she flew to California and Las Vegas accompanied only
by White House photographer and a trip coordinator. The cost of
operating that C-32 is even higher than the C-20, which costs
$3,705 per hour to fly. Kolbe estimates that West Coast trip at
$123,000. Clinton's campaign reimbursed $3,723.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1843 </TRAILER>
