<HEADLINE> Motorist admits he made false charges after vehicle stop caught on tape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - An East Orange man has admitted he lied
when he filed formal charges that state troopers were abusive and
threatening during a motor vehicle stop.
</P>
<P>
   An internal affairs investigation used tape from the patrol
car's video camera as evidence against the motorist.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras were installed in State Police vehicles after reports
from motorists that troopers who targeted minority drivers were
sometimes abusive.
</P>
<P>
   Moses E. Cobb, 65, pleaded guilty to filing a false report,
state police Col. Carson Dunbar said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal Court Judge Richard W. Krater sentenced Cobb to 30
days community service and a 60-day suspended jail sentence. Cobb
was also told the pay $555 in fines and court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb first complained of the alleged abuse on May 10 of last
year in a letter to State Police supervisors, according to a
statement from Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, he had been stopped on the New Jersey Turnpike
near Exit 9 for speeding by two troopers, Dunbar's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb complained that the troopers stopped him for no reason.
Cobb also said one officer approached him with his hand on his
weapon, leaned in the car and then spit on a female passenger,
according to Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   The video tape did not back Cobb's statements, according to the
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras are now installed in 785 cars assigned to the turnpike,
the Garden State Parkway and the Atlantic City Expressway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
