<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Dutch Talks at White House  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Dutch Prime Minister Wim
Kok held a White House meeting Thursday on issues ranging from the
elections in Serbia to the illicit import of the drug ecstasy into
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president indicated that for a relatively small country
the Netherlands has a tremendous footprint in terms of its impact
within NATO and around the world,'' said P.J. Crowley, spokesman
for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   First in the Oval Office, then over lunch in the White House,
the two leaders discussed an array of issues, problems and sources
of concern around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Both agreed that the opposition political party in Yugoslavia
was the clear victor in this week's elections and that it is time
for Serbian president Slobodan Milosevic to concede defeat and step
aside, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   International sanctions against Serbia will be lifted once a
democratically elected government is in place, Kok and Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands will take its turn as president of the United
Nations Security Council in November and Kok told Clinton that he
wishes to focus on Africa, including the situation in Sierra Leone,
Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the discussions, Crowley said the two leaders agreed
it would be best that lingering trade disputes with the European
Union be settled before they poison relations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
   And Crowley said Kok and Clinton also noted that 60 percent to
80 percent of the illegal drug ecstasy reaching the United States
originates in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The two said the issue would be discussed further in November at
a conference between representatives of the two country's Justice
ministries.
</P>
</TEXT>
