<HEADLINE> Joyce weakens slightly, Isaac regains major hurricane status  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) - Hurricane Joyce kept marching westward across the
Atlantic Thursday with top sustained winds of 85 mph, but wasn't
expected to get any stronger through most of Friday, forecasters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hurricane Isaac's top sustained winds jumped from 120
mph to 140 mph late Thursday as the system swirled across the open
sea about 1,250 miles north-northwest of Joyce, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither system posed any immediate threat to land.
</P>
<P>
   ''Isaac is no threat to any land in the foreseeable future,''
said Jack Beven, a hurricane specialist at the National Hurricane
Center in Miami. ''Joyce could be a threat to the Caribbean islands
several days away, but it's too early to say with any certainty
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce, which became a tropical storm Monday and a hurricane
Wednesday, was expected to start turning north in several days,
said hurricane specialist James Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we don't know is how sharp that turn will be,'' he said.
Sharp enough, and it could miss the Caribbean altogether and stay
over open waters.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. EDT, Joyce was centered near 11.1 north latitude, 45.8
west longitude or about 920 miles east of the Windward Islands. It
was moving west-southwest at about 14 mph.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching top winds of 120 mph Saturday, Isaac lost power
for several days as other weather systems began affecting it. It
cleared those systems and rebuilding began Wednesday as a major
storm.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. EDT, Isaac was near 27.4 north latitude, 54.7 west
longitude, or about 690 miles east-southeast of Bermuda. It was
moving northwest at near 20 mph, with a turn northward forecast
during the coming 24 hours. Forecasters said it should pass well
east of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
