<DOCNO> APW20000928.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Gets Final Say Over Release  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Commerce Secretary Norman Mineta on Thursday
gave the Census Bureau the authority to decide whether to release
sampled Census 2000 data that could drastically affect how states
redraw political lines next year.
</P>
<P>
   The decision whether to issue raw population counts adjusted
using the statistical method known as sampling should be made ''by
the experts at the bureau,'' Mineta said in a statement. ''This
regulation is designed to ensure that politics are not a part of
this important decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule takes effect 30 days after its publication in the
Federal Register. The authority had previously been with the
Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   By Dec. 31, the Census Bureau must release its first population
count, which the Supreme Court said last year must be used for
reapportioning the 435 House seats among states. The first count is
based on forms households mailed back to the bureau, and visits
that census-takers made to homes that did not return a form.
</P>
<P>
   The same court decision left it up to states to decide whether
to use sampled data when redistricting. Supporters say sampling
will help account for parts of the population missed in prior
counts, including minorities, the poor and inner-city residents
that traditionally vote Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, in general, say the agency's plan is flawed, and
fear using the sampled numbers could skew redrawn districts in
Democrats' favor.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Walker, spokesman for Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of
the House Government Reform Committee's census panel, called the
decision Thursday ''purely a political move that does nothing than
to remove the decision from one Clinton appointee in place with
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census director's position and the Commerce Department
secretary are politically appointed positions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
