<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Subpoena seeking acid report issued  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - A leading House Republican subpoenaed the
Environmental Protection Agency on Thursday to obtain a long sought
report on acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials said they would provide the report but were
working out the details of how to do so.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of New York lawmakers have been seeking the report -
a cost benefit analysis of acid rain reduction bills - for six
months. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan first requested the cost
review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   EPA completed it in March but it has been sitting in the Office
of Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan along with Republican Reps. Sherwood Boehlert and John
Sweeney are the main sponsors of legislation to reduce emissions of
the acid rain-causing pollutants nitrogen and sulfur.
</P>
<P>
   The New York lawmakers are hopeful the report will provide them
with ammunition to push legislation unpopular with Midwestern
lawmakers through Congress. Much of the nitrogen and sulfur
pollution originates at Midwestern coal burning plants and is then
carried east on prevailing winds.
</P>
<P>
   Letters asking that the report be made public were ignored by
OMB, the New York lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John McHugh asked Rep. Dan Burton, chairman of the
Committee on Government Reform, to issue a subpoena for the report.
The Indiana Republican agreed. Burton's committee includes
oversight of the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are issuing this subpoena because we need to bring acid
rain under control. Apparently, it's going to take a subpoena to
get the administration to do its part,'' McHugh said.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials said they were always intent on cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to move this through as soon as possible,'' EPA
Associate Deputy Administrator Dawn Martin said. ''We're feeling
the need to be responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's once-pristine Adirondack Mountains have been hit
particularly hard by acid rain, which is caused when nitrogen and
sulfur in the smog mix with airborne moisture and fall as rain or
snow.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report from the U.S. General Accounting Office found
that mountain soil in the Adirondack State Park isn't absorbing
nitrogen oxide, so it is flowing directly into waterways and ponds
and causing them to die at a quicker rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a wide body of evidence that the effects of acid rain
are worsening,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   New York State has sued 14 out-of-state utilities demanding that
they modify their facilities to operate in compliance with the
federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 1932 </TRAILER>
