<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel Approves Rail Bill  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee approved a bill Thursday
that would raise benefits for retired rail workers and cut taxes
for railroads while also draining $15 billion from the budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after senators rejected an attempt to attach an
unrelated measure expanding Medicaid coverage for severely disabled
children.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an avalanche of amendments forced the Senate Finance
Committee to give up on a 10-year, $38.7 billion bill using tax
breaks and regulatory relief to spur investment in impoverished
inner cities and rural areas. A slimmed-down version of that bill,
the outgrowth of a deal between President Clinton and House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is still likely to emerge before Congress
adjourns for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers met for
nearly two hours with House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, to
begin work toward a compromise tax relief package likely to include
the anti-poverty measures.
</P>
<P>
   No decisions were made, but aides said other items likely to be
included in the 10-year, roughly $300 billion package include
repeal of the federal telephone excise tax, a pension bill that
expands contributions to IRAs and 401(k) plans and a series of tax
breaks for business to offset the cost of a potential $1 increase
in the $5.15-an-hour minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   With the congressional session winding down, senators on the
Finance Committee were looking Thursday to attach their priority
bills to any legislation with a decent chance of becoming law. The
railroad retirement bill, which passed the House earlier this month
on a 391-25 vote, is one of those measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's probably the last train out of the station,'' said Sen.
John Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said thousands of children with
severe disabilities and their parents could be helped by his
legislation ensuring that they could continue government Medicaid
health coverage even if their incomes rose above the program's
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's wrong for families to have to impoverish themselves
because they love their kids and want to take care of their health
needs,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the bill has 77 Senate co-sponsors -- and senators
were extremely reluctant to vote against such an emotional issue --
opponents pointed out that it could benefit families earning up to
$84,000 a year and consume $11 billion of the projected budget
surplus over the next decade. Grassley's effort to attach it to the
railroad bill failed on a 10-7 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have let this surplus burn a hole in our pocket and turn
out the lights in our heads,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ''I
just think this is completely out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The railroad retirement overhaul, which cleared the Finance
Committee on a voice vote, arose from two years of negotiations
between railroads and 13 unions representing about 250,000 workers
and 650,000 retirees, widows and dependents. Among other things,
the legislation would permit the transfer of $15 billion from a
Depression-era government pension fund into a new privately
administered account that would be invested in stocks, bonds and
other securities.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 8 percent return on investment, sponsors say,
would finance an increase in benefits for rail retirees, including
reduction of retirement age from 62 to 60, and cut payroll taxes
for railroads by $400 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer would consume more than half the $28 billion in
fiscal 2001 surplus dollars that Republicans want to use for tax
reduction or more spending, said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla. But the
committee rebuffed his effort to delay the effective date until
2002; sponsors say the hit on the surplus is a one-time cost
associated with the redeeming of Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nickles expressed concern that Congress was setting the
federal government up for a huge bailout, or a massive payroll tax
increase on the railroads, if the pension investments failed to
meet expectations. The White House has also raised concerns about
the precedent for Social Security, where there are several
proposals to shift funds into private investments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Expanding benefits and cutting taxes is not financially
sound,'' Nickles said. ''I think it's irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
