<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Crisp, fall weather dominated much of the nation
Thursday, while
showers fell in Florida.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cold front stretched from northerain New England, to the
mid-Atlantic into the Ohio Valley bringing mostly cloudy but dry
conditions. Temperatures in the Upper Midwest and Great Lakes
dipped into the 20s overainight.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms fell in central and southerain Florida.
Fort Lauderdale received three-quarters of an inch of rain, and
other areas had a half-inch. The remainder of the Southeast was
clear.
</P>
<P>
   An upper level low off the Califorainia coast brought isolated
showers to mountainous areas of Arizona and New Mexico. The Pacific
Northwest was cloudy. The remainder of the West was partly cloudy
to clear.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Lower 48 states Thursday ranged from a
midday high of 92 degrees in Gila Bend, Ariz., to a moraining low of
19 degrees in Pellston, Mich. The wind made the temperature in
Frenchville, Maine, feel like 13 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service:
http://iwin.nws.noaa.gov/iwin/graphicsversion/bigmain.html
