<DOCNO> APW20000928.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nader Candidate Does Letterman  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ralph Nader may not have been invited to next
week's presidential debate, but at least he made it to Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party presidential candidate took his spot in the hot
seat on ''Late Night with David Letterman'' on Thursday, talking
about what his party stands for, the environment and his take on
the two main party candidates, Republican George W. Bush and
Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On Bush: ''George W. Bush is really a big corporation running
for president disguised as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   On Gore: ''Al Gore's dilemma every day on the campaign trail is
to figure out whether he's the 'Great Impostor' or the 'Great
Pretender.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore have appeared on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Nader criticized Gore's environmental record as vice president
and said he didn't believe Gore would do any better as president.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman asked whether voting for the Green Party would be
wasting a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Throwing away your vote is throwing away your vote in the
direction of the two major parties that have wasted our democracy,
that are excluding competitors in the presidential debates,'' Nader
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Nader will not participate in Tuesday's debate in Boston because
he failed to meet the criteria for inclusion set by the bipartisan
Commission on Presidential Debates.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates must appear on enough state ballots to have a chance
of winning the election and must have an average of 15 percent
support in five major national polls, according to commission.
Nader has been in the low single digits in these surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters have protested his exclusion. About 50 people
gathered outside the theater before Thursday's taping, carrying
signs that said ''Let Ralph Debate'' and ''Be a genius. Think for
yourself. Vote Nader.'' They also plan to rally in Boston two days
before the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The pull-no-punches Letterman was even blunter in his last
question for Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't win,'' he said. ''What is your goal?''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to get millions of votes, and after November, the
Green Party will be building,'' Nader said. ''It will be a watchdog
on the two parties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 1957 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
