<HEADLINE> House: Reject China 2008 Olympic Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House resolution was introduced Thursday
urging that Beijing not be selected as host of the 2008 Olympics
unless human rights conditions improve in China.
</P>
<P>
   ''The human rights record of the People's Republic of China is
abominable -- and it is getting worse, not better,'' said Rep. Tom
Lantos, D-Calif., who introduced the bill. ''It is completely
inconsistent with the Olympic ideal to hold the games in Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing is one of five cities being considered by the
International Olympic Committee, which is to decide in July on a
venue for the 2008 games.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution sites ''deplorable'' human rights abuses such as
censorship, torture and mistreatment of prisoners, violence against
women, child abuse and denial of freedom of religion and assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But the resolution praises Chinese Olympic athletes now
participating in Sydney, Australia, noting they have placed third
in the number of metals earned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thousands of Chinese athletes have shown their strong support
for the Olympic spirit through their commitment to excellence,
energy, skill sportsmanship and good will towards their fellow
athletes,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the House would have time to vote on the
measure before it adjourns, probably in mid-October.
</P>
</TEXT>
