<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six more West Nile-infected crows found in Baltimore  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX DOMINGUEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) - Six more dead crows found across the city have
tested positive for the mosquito-borne West Nile virus that can be
fatal to humans, state officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the crows were infected in Maryland is not known, but
none of the mosquitoes tested in the state so far have been
infected with the virus, said J.B. Hanson, a spokesman for the
state health department.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know what the point of origin is,'' Hanson said.
''They could have been from Massachusetts, Canada, New York, New
Jersey. We just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus caused the Sept. 14 death of an 82-year-old
New Jersey man - the first such death in the United States this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The virus also has been detected in birds in New York,
Connecticut, Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Pennsylvania. A total
of 17 people have been infected.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the virus killed seven people in the New York
metropolitan area. No human cases have been reported in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The six latest Baltimore crows were received by state health
officials on Monday for testing. The positive test results followed
last week's announcement three crows found in the Federal Hill
neighborhood and in Baltimore County and Howard County were also
infected.
</P>
<P>
   State officials sprayed parts of Baltimore County and Howard
County to kill mosquitoes that may be carrying the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The state also planned to spray the city's downtown area and
nearby neighborhoods, but canceled the spraying because of cold
weather that made the insecticide Permethrin less effective. The
spraying has been criticized by some who claim Permethrin poses a
greater health risk than the virus itself.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials said the spraying will continue, perhaps on
a larger scale, when possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, when weather permits, spraying will continue in an
effort to decrease the mosquito population,'' Hanson said. ''As it
stands, the weather's been too cold to do any significant spraying,
or it's been raining.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a lot of areas to deal with now, that's why we've
got to assess this to find the best mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   The virus, transmitted through mosquito bites, can cause
encephalitis - the swelling of the brain - and meningitis - the
swelling of the lining of the brain and spinal cord - in humans.
</P>
<P>
   While those diseases can be fatal, the very young and the very
old are the most at risk, health officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Health Commissioner Peter Beilenson urged residents
not to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is the same. This is not a very serious virus
or illness,'' he said. ''The vast majority of the people, even if
they did get bitten by a mosquito are not even going to develop
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The few that develop symptoms, it will be like a normal flu.''
</P>
<P>
   State health officials again urged residents to eliminate
standing water in which mosquitoes can breed and to wear long
sleeves and pants when going outside at dusk or dawn, when
mosquitoes are most active.
</P>
<P>
   The threat from the virus subsides once cold weather arrives and
the mosquitoes become dormant, state officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 2103 </TRAILER>
