<HEADLINE> Lieberman Criticizes GOP Drug Plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman, flanked by longtime congressional colleagues, on
Thursday accused Republicans of ''downright deceptive'' claims
about their plans for drug coverage for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the Capitol steps, Lieberman said the plan backed by
Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush would ''leave behind
more than half of all senior citizens who have coverage today.'' By
contrast, he said, Al Gore and the Democrats want to offer
protection under Medicare to ''every single senior citizen and
person with disability in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Republicans accused President Clinton and the
Democrats of stalling.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert said GOP leaders had made a ''good
effort at trying to do some things to help our seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, ''We're calling on the
president to work with us on getting prescription drug help for
seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's appearance marked a rare drop-by at the Capitol for
Gore's running mate. His limousine, parked a few feet away,
underscored his new status after 12 years as a rank-and-file
senator from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance billed as a ''unity'' rally, House Democratic
Leader Dick Gephardt and Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle
heaped criticism on congressional Republicans, and said Democrats
would press for passage of a prescription drug plan under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a group of Republican leaders in Congress who do not
like Medicare, who have never liked Medicare, and a group that
doesn't want prescription drugs delivered through Medicare,'' said
Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle accused Republicans of spending millions of dollars on
''misleading campaign ads'' designed to persuade voters the GOP
favors a prescription drug bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said millions of ''middle class Americans are going to
be left without prescription drug coverage'' under Bush's plan.
While Bush criticizes Gore's proposal as a government-run HMO,
Lieberman said the GOP's own claims are ''downright deceptive'' in
the political marketplace of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a Democratic National Committee fund-raiser that was
raising more than $1 million for the party, Lieberman listed what
he said were economic achievements by Clinton and Gore and said:
''That doesn't happen by accident and it won't continue by
inertia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
