<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: N. Ireland Involvement Good  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Thursday he was glad he
decided to involve the United States in the Northern Ireland peace
process, calling the decision ''a sea change in American foreign
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at a fund-raiser for Rep. Richard Neil, D-Mass., a
strong backer of the peace accords who praised Clinton for going
against the wishes of the State Department and granting a visa to
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The president said it ''was a sea change in American foreign
policy getting involved in the Irish peace process. We're not
entirely there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He thanked those on stage with him for their support, including
Neil, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and a Republican, Rep. Peter
King of New York, who is a friend of Neil.
</P>
<P>
   The president went through a litany of his campaign
accomplishments, and urged the crowd to return congressional
Democrats to the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my lifetime, we never had a chance like this. We never had
so much prosperity and social progress, and the absence of an
internal crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neil, first elected in 1988, is unopposed in his re-election
race.
</P>
</TEXT>
