<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Raps Bush As Well As Gore  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John McCain said Thursday ''it was a mistake''
for George W. Bush to reject his challenge to ban soft money from
the presidential race against Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers said they were frustrated with McCain for forcing
the issue of campaign finance reform into the race by seeking a
voluntary ban on the unlimited, unregulated donations. Gore
accepted McCain's proposal, and Republican strategists said the
whole episode could complicate Bush's efforts -- just as he has been
rising in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing back into the political ring after a cancer scare, the
Arizona senator has seized the spotlight with attacks against bad
movies, flawed tires, wasteful spending and, most notably, the
fund-raising practices of both presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting a soft money ban ''would have been a major step toward
ridding the political system of its most pernicious evil -- and
that's unregulated donations,'' the senator said Thursday in a
telephone interview that also included a harsh assessment of Gore's
''reprehensible'' record on campaign fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   After Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican Rep. Rick
Lazio agreed to ban soft money from their New York senate race,
McCain and Democratic Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin decided to
seek voluntary bans in all federal races, including the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A letter proposing the ban was sent to both Gore and Bush with
little notice before it became public -- a point that upset some
senior campaign advisers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore quickly accepted. McCain's advisers said they urged Bush's
team to enter into discussions about a possible ban to keep Gore
from grandstanding on the issue, but the idea was firmly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have liked for him to accept our offer and I feel it
was a mistake not to,'' McCain said in an interview arranged by
aides to discuss his post-surgery agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll continue to try'' to get soft money out of the
presidential race, ''but obviously we were dealt a setback'' by
Bush, said McCain, who gave Bush his stiffest challenge in this
year's GOP primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that for one thing, he wasn't sure he could trust Gore
to live up to any such agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Thursday the offer was still open and that having
McCain and Feingold as ''arbiters'' of any deal should erase
questions about trust.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does he trust John McCain and Russ Feingold?'' Gore
rhetorically asked in an appearance on CNN's ''Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   On a related matter, Gore shrugged off questions raised about
overnight visits in the White House by financial contributors to
President Clinton and his wife, Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would allow such visits if he wins the election, he
said: ''If somebody is a close friend who is also a campaign
supporter, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed if he would do the same for someone who is a financial
contributor but not a close friend, Gore hesitated, shrugged and
said no.
</P>
<P>
   Saving his harshest criticism for the vice president, McCain
dismissed suggestions that Gore would benefit from accepting the
ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vice president's record on this is reprehensible. They've
debased the institutions of government and that kind of activity
continues with Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is renting out the
Lincoln bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers said privately that McCain gave Gore an opening to
throw the Texan off-message and inoculate himself against the
Clinton-Gore fund-raising controversies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather be talking about education reform and issues that
count,'' said Ron Kaufman, former political director for President
Bush and a Washington ally of the Texas governor. Still, he said
voters will view Gore's pledge as insincere and ''this McCain thing
could backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush to accept the ban would be a strategic mistake, GOP
analysts said, because the most recent financial reports show Gore
with a $10 million cash advantage; that means Bush is more reliant
than Gore on soft money spending by the GOP and outside interest
groups. In addition, the GOP has a multimillion dollar soft money
advantage over the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Wednesday he would consider a voluntary ban but
expressed strong skepticism that Gore would live up to the
agreement, and aides said the remarks amounted to a rejection of
McCain's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor wants to ban soft money but there's no reason to
believe Al Gore would abide by a handshake agreement when he has a
hard time abiding by the laws of the land,'' said Ed Gillespie, a
top Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who said he is fully recovered from skin cancer surgery,
said the soft money fight is only part of his agenda as chairman of
the Commerce Committee. He said he's also focused on improving the
way Hollywood markets its entertainment to youngsters and the
investigation into fatal accidents involving Firestone tires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
