<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Sept. 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA Approves Abortion Pill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Capping a bitter 12-year battle, the government today
approved use of the abortion pill RU-486, a major victory for abortion-rights
advocates that could dramatically alter abortion in this country. The
long-expected decision by the Food and Drug Administration allows Americans an
early-abortion method already used in France, Britain, China and 10 other
countries. The action is expected to make abortion in the United States more
accessible and more private.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Voters Reject Euro in Denmark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Danish voters on Thursday rejected the European
Union's common currency in favor of keeping the 125-year-old krone. The
referendum -- closely watched because Britain, Sweden and Greece also plan votes
on euro adoption -- was an embarrassment to the European Union which has pressed
for a monetary union. ''The Commission regrets this decision,'' said Romano
Prodi, president of the EU's executive commission. ''I firmly believe that a
positive vote would have been in our common interest.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former Canadian PM Trudeau Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Former Prime Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau, a flamboyant
and charismatic political giant who led the country through some of its most
tumultuous events, died today. He was 80. Trudeau died of prostate cancer, said
Roy Heenan, senior partner of the Montreal law firm Heenan Blaikie, where
Trudeau worked.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Approves Energy-Water Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a $23.6 billion measure for water and
energy programs today, steering lawmakers toward a veto fight with President
Clinton that each party thinks may help it win the White House. House-Senate
negotiators also reached an agreement on a new, six-year land conservation
program that would eventually grow to about $2.4 billion a year, clearing the
way for passage next week of another of the 11 spending bills still unfinished
as the new fiscal year begins.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maximum Age at Death Trending Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the 1860s, the oldest person to die each year in Sweden
was about 100. Last year, that age had risen to 108. Researchers are finding
this trend in all industrialized countries and say the very old may get even
older. Plotting the increasing maximum age of death among the Swedes, says
researcher John R. Wilmoth, suggests the life span of humans is expanding and
that there is no clear upper limit. Wilmoth, a researcher at the University of
California, Berkeley is first author of a study appearing Friday in the journal
Science.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Venezuela To Subpoena Ford Execs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela said Thursday it will subpoena
executives from the subsidiaries of Ford Motor Co. and Bridgestone/Firestone
Inc. as it investigates fatal accidents involving Ford sport utility vehicles
equipped with Firestone tires. Indecu, Venezuela's consumer protection agency,
said it will issue the subpoenas Friday. Venezuela's attorney general gave the
agency powers last week to investigate accidents involving Ford Explorers
mounted with Bridgestone/Firestone tires. Ford insists its vehicles are safe and
contends tire tread separation was a common factor in accidents that killed at
least 46 people in Venezuela.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately Friday, lifted by a rally in
stocks on Wall Street. The Nikkei gained 146.37 points to 15,773.33 points in
early trading. In New York, the buying of technology issues led early gains in
other stocks as investors were cheered up by an 122.72-point rise in the Nasdaq
composite index, which finished at 3,778.32. The Dow rose 195.70 points to close
at 10,824.06.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Women Advance To Relay Semis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- While Marion Jones rested for the long jump final
later in the day, her teammates on the injury-depleted U.S. women's 400-meter
relay squad advanced to the semifinals by easily winning their first-round heat.
A team of Chryste Gaines, Torri Edwards, Nanceen Perry and Passion Richardson
won its heat Friday (Thursday night EDT) in 42.92 seconds. Also advancing were
top rivals Jamaica and the Bahamas, but Australia dropped its baton and was
ousted. The relay semifinals were set for later in the day.
</P>
