<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Congress To Dismantle Agency  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The Peruvian Congress voted to dismantle the
country's National Intelligence Service, which for a decade served
as the power base of now-exiled spy chief Vladimiro Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on Thursday voted 101 to one, with one abstention, to
deactivate within 15 days what has become Peru's most vilified
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the vote, some 2,500 laborers, teachers and students
marched to the Government Palace, demanding President Alberto
Fujimori's immediate resignation and the extradition of his
intelligence adviser from Panama to face corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   The march, the largest of several demonstrations Thursday in
Peru's major cities, was peaceful. Riot police lined the front
gates of the palace while banner-waving protesters chanted
''Justice and jail for the Mafioso Montesinos.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There is widespread corruption, so deeply institutionalized
that this government no longer makes sense,'' said Jose Luis Risco,
president of the General Confederation of Peruvian Workers, an
umbrella group of unions and labor federations.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's spy agency administered an extensive intelligence network
credited by many with crippling leftist insurgencies and combatting
narcotics trafficking in the early years of Fujimori's decade in
power. But in recent years, it earned a darker reputation as a
Gestapo-like police force, accused of human rights abuses and of
bending Peru's democratic institutions to Fujimori's will.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori announced Sept. 16 that he was ending his 10-year
presidency with new elections and would call for the deactivation
of Montesinos' espionage agency after a videotape showed the
intelligence adviser apparently bribing an opposition lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The decision caused an apparent power struggle between Fujimori
and his once-trusted aide, who fled Peru on Sunday to seek
political asylum in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 lawmakers have abandoned Fujimori's Peru 2000 party
since the corruption scandal began, depriving him of the majority
in the 120-seat legislature that he has used for most of the last
decade to pass laws at will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
