<HEADLINE> Monroe Independence Party leader to quit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The chairman of the Monroe County
Independence Party said he's quitting the party he helped launch to
join the growing ranks of unaffiliated American voters.
</P>
<P>
   David Stockmeister of Rochester on Thursday called the
Democratic and Republican parties mirror images of one another and
said the national Reform Party the Independents had been associated
with was ''a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Independence Party had proven no better, and that he
had decided to register blank for next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   ''The party seems to have gravitated toward an affection with
Lenora Fulani who has declared herself a Marxist,'' he said. ''I do
not wish to be affiliated with or associated with that element.''
Fulani has been a perennial candidate of the left-leaning New
Alliance Party for everything from governor to president.
</P>
<P>
   Stockmeister was key among those who founded what became the
state's third largest political party in Rochester in 1994. The
party was meant to offer a middle-of-the-road alternative to
traditional conservative or liberal views.
</P>
<P>
   His decision follows Sunday's statewide Independence Party
meeting, which he did not attend. The meeting ended with party
members giving their presidential ballet line to John Hagelin of
Fairfield, Iowa and then voting to sever all ties with the national
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals for the ballet line had included Ralph Nader and Pat
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   State party chairman Frank MacKay of Suffolk County said he was
saddened by Stockmeister's decision but downplayed Fulani's role in
it. In reality, MacKay said, the decision was a reflection of the
party's expansion beyond its Rochester roots to include downstate
members such as Fulani.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now it's spread out and the balance of power is
excellent,'' Mackay said.
</P>
</TEXT>
