<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despite more dead crows, state says West Nile virus has not spread  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - More dead crows infected with the West Nile
virus have been found, but state health officials said Thursday the
fatal disease has not spread in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   An 82-year-old man from Little Falls in Passaic County was the
first person in the nation to die from the mosquito-borne disease
this year. State officials announced his death Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another person is being tested for the disease. That brings the
total number of human patients who have been tested for the virus
to 39, Health Department officials announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Four people including the man who died Sept. 14 have tested
positive. Another 16 were cleared and 19 are still waiting for
results.
</P>
<P>
   All those tested had symptoms of the disease and all are from
areas in New Jersey where the virus has been found in animals or
mosquito pools.
</P>
<P>
   Infected crows have been found in 16 of the state's 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   Six horses have also tested positive, two each in Atlantic and
Sussex counties and one each in Cape May and Ocean counties.
</P>
<P>
   State labs logged 93 more infected crows, bringing the total to
931 birds, Health Department spokesman Dennis McGowan said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   All of those crows were found in counties that already have
reported infected birds, McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials expect reports of the virus to drop as the
temperatures do the same, McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It does help. Mosquitoes become less active in cool weather,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, the first hard frost will officially end the
season,'' McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims in New Jersey are a 72-year-old Bayonne woman, a
43-year-old Jersey City man and a 54-year-old man with dual
residency in Brooklyn, N.Y., and Cliffside Park.
</P>
<P>
   There have been seven cases of human infection in New York City
this year. The virus caused 62 human cases of encephalitis and
seven deaths in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are urged to protect themselves from mosquito bites by
wearing long clothing and insect repellant. People have been told
to clear all pools of standing water where mosquitoes breed.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is transmitted through the bite of mosquitoes, which
acquire it by feeding on infected birds. Generally, it causes
flulike symptoms or no problems at all, but it can be dangerous to
young children, the elderly and anyone with a weakened immune
system.
</P>
<P>
   Little Falls Mayor Eugene Kulick announced officials will hold a
town meeting Saturday at the municipal building to address concerns
about the local man's death from the virus. Local and state health
officials will answer residents' questions.
</P>
<P>
   All 21 counties in the state have increased mosquito-control
efforts, state officials said. Many of those programs include
spraying pesticides to kill the mosquitoes at various stages of
development.
</P>
<P>
   Infected birds have been found in Bergen (188), Burlington (6),
Camden (3), Cape May (2), Essex (94), Gloucester (2), Hudson (61),
Hunterdon (3), Mercer (7), Middlesex (199), Monmouth (139), Morris
(33), Ocean (11), Passaic (69), Somerset (16) and Union (98)
counties.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.http://www.state.nj.us/health/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-28-00 2227 </TRAILER>
