<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Sept. 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Voters Reject Euro in Denmark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Favoring the 125-year old krone, Danish voters on
Thursday rejected the European Union's common currency. The referendum --
closely watched because Britain, Sweden and Greece also plan votes on euro
adoption -- was an embarrassment to the European Union which has pressed for a
monetary union. ''The Commission regrets this decision,'' said Romano Prodi,
president of the EU's executive commission. ''I firmly believe that a positive
vote would have been in our common interest.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA OKs Abortion Pill RU-486
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government today approved use of the abortion pill
RU-486, capping a bitter 12-year battle. The pill is a major victory for
abortion-rights advocates that could dramatically alter abortion in this
country. The long-expected decision by the Food and Drug Administration allows
Americans an early-abortion method already used in France, Britain, China and 10
other countries. The action is expected to make abortion in the United States
more accessible and more private.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former Canadian PM Trudeau Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Former Prime Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau, a flamboyant
and charismatic politician who led Canada through some of its most tumultuous
events, died today. He was 80. Trudeau died of prostate cancer, said Roy Heenan,
senior partner of the Montreal law firm Heenan Blaikie, where Trudeau worked. He
said Trudeau's health had declined ''very steadily'' in his final days.
Trudeau's sons Justin and Sacha Trudeau confirmed their father's death.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge: 2 Claims Out in Tobacco Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge today dismissed half of the claims in the
Clinton administration's massive lawsuit against cigarette makers but still let
the government seek billions from the industry for allegedly concealing the
dangers of smoking. In a ruling praised by both sides, U.S. District Judge
Gladys Kessler decided the government could pursue racketeering claims seeking
to force the industry to hand over profits dating back to the 1950s. But she
also said the government could not invoke two federal laws to recover the
Medicare cost of treating ill smokers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peru Congress To Dismantle Agency
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The Peruvian Congress voted to dismantle the country's
National Intelligence Service, which for a decade served as the power base of
now-exiled spy chief Vladimiro Montesinos. Lawmakers on Thursday voted 101 to
one, with one abstention, to deactivate within 15 days what has become Peru's
most vilified institution. Hours after the vote, some 2,500 laborers, teachers
and students marched to the Government Palace, demanding President Alberto
Fujimori's immediate resignation and the extradition of his intelligence adviser
from Panama to face corruption charges.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Paul Allen Quits Microsoft Board
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Paul Allen is leaving Microsoft's board of directors
but will remain an adviser to Bill Gates, the prep school buddy with whom he
co-founded the company. Allen, the world's third-richest man with an estimated
net worth of $36 billion, will spend about the same amount of time working with
Microsoft, but will focus less on business and more on technology, the company
said today. Allen will formally leave the board on Nov. 9, the day of
Microsoft's annual shareholders' meeting.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately Friday, lifted by a rally in
stocks on Wall Street. The Nikkei gained 146.37 points to 15,773.33 points in
early trading. In New York, the buying of technology issues led early gains in
other stocks as investors were cheered up by an 122.72-point rise in the Nasdaq
composite index, which finished at 3,778.32. The Dow rose 195.70 points to close
at 10,824.06.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Women Advance To Relay Semis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- While Marion Jones rested for the long jump final
later in the day, her teammates on the injury-depleted U.S. women's 400-meter
relay squad advanced to the semifinals by easily winning their first-round heat.
A team of Chryste Gaines, Torri Edwards, Nanceen Perry and Passion Richardson
won its heat Friday (Thursday night EDT) in 42.92 seconds. Also advancing were
top rivals Jamaica and the Bahamas, but Australia dropped its baton and was
ousted. The relay semifinals were set for later in the day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Orioles Defeat Blue Jays 23-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Delino DeShields homered and had a career-high five RBIs as
the Baltimore Orioles eliminated the Toronto Blue Jays from the postseason race
with a record-setting 23-1 rout tonight. The 23 runs scored by Baltimore broke a
team mark, set June 13, 1999 at Atlanta in a 22-1 victory. The Orioles raked
four Blue Jays pitchers for 23 hits.
AP NewsBrief By MARIA CODER 
</P>
