<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Kayaker Still Under Probe  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENRITH, Australia (AP) -- The International Canoe Federation
said it has run into nothing but dead-ends as it investigates
allegations of drug use by a Bulgarian kayaker who is a finalist in
three Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
   ICF president Ulrich Feldhoff said he was turning over all he
has learned to the International Olympic Committee, but wasn't
confident that agency could do any better.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the IOC, there is the same problem that we have,''
Feldhoff said at a news conference Friday (Thursday night EDT).
''Without written evidence, it is impossible to take any action.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC said it had no knowledge of the case of Peter Merkov.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of today, as I speak, there is absolutely no case
concerning this athlete. We have nothing on the table,'' said
Francois Carrard, the IOC's general secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulgarian newspaper 24 Hours reported two weeks ago that
Merkov and two teammates tested positive for a diuretic that's
banned because it can be used to cover up steroid use. The test
reportedly was taken at the national championships in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Slavkov, an IOC member from Bulgaria who leads his
country's delegation to the games, told the ICF he has never
received that information from the Bulgarian anti-doping agency.
</P>
<P>
   Feldhoff released a letter in which Slavkov wrote, ''The
Bulgarian Olympic Committee has not received any official
information from the Bulgarian Anti-Doping Commission. It is rather
surprising that your request is based on a newspaper article.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bulgarian team manager Victor Kirin: ''They usually send a
letter when it's positive. When it's negative, they don't send a
letter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Feldhoff said Bulgarian reporters told the federation the
test results were announced by the anti-doping commission at a news
conference in Bulgaria. His attempts to reach the commission have
been fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ''For three days now, I have tried by fax to get an answer from
the anti-doping commission of Bulgaria. We've received no answer,''
Feldhoff said. ''Since yesterday, we have tried to make telephone
contact with those responsible for the anti-doping commission. That
also has been unsuccessful. The two telephone numbers that have
been given to us have been continuously engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Verstuyft, the chairman of the ICF's medical committee, said
the ICF can't ask the Bulgarian doctor in Sydney about the results
because proper channels must be followed.
</P>
<P>
   He added that even if the IOC is able to get information from
the Bulgarians, it isn't completely reliable because the testing
facility is not among the IOC's 25 accredited labs.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's another problem,'' Verstuyft said. ''We don't know who
they are, how they work, what their independency or transparency
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Merkov, meanwhile, advanced to the finals in the solo 500- and
1,000-meter races and in the four-man event. The K-1 1,000 and the
K-4 will be decided Saturday (Friday night EDT). The K-1 500 finals
are on Sunday (Saturday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Merkov won his 500 semifinal heat Friday, then shouted to
reporters: ''I'll talk after the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Merkov has not had any positive tests in Sydney, Verstuyft said.
</P>
<P>
   The other two accused Bulgarians are Marian Dimitrov, who failed
to make the finals in the 1,000-meter K-2, and Moetceo Tchalakov,
who the team said did not compete in Sydney because of health
reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 2314 </TRAILER>
