<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disposal Lighters Being Recalled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Atlanta company is recalling about 350,000
disposable cigarette lighters because they can burn with high flame
and fail to extinguish, posing fire and burn hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said Thursday the agency
and Halpern Import Co. have received one report of a woman who
received second-degree burns on her chest when the lighter failed
to extinguish and ignited her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The lighters are oval-tube shaped and have a green, red, blue,
black or yellow body and a metal top. They have ''TURBO 2000''
printed on them, and a label reads: ''CHILD-RESISTANT DISPOSABLE
LIGHTER,'' ''KEEP OUT OF REACH OF CHILDREN,'' and ''MADE IN
CHINA.''
</P>
<P>
   The UPC number 0 80692 05010 1 is printed on the back of the
lighters.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco and thrift stores nationwide sold the lighters from June
1999 through May 2000 for about $1.
</P>
<P>
   The CPSC advised consumers to immediately stop using the
lighters and return them to the store where they were purchased for
a refund. For more information, consumers can call 1-800-624-5280
between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m. EDT Monday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Consumer Product Safety Commission:
http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
