<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Peruvian Spy Chief Arranges Photo  </HEADLINE>
By KATHIA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Panamanians caught their first
glimpse of ex-Peruvian spy chief Vladimiro Montesinos on Thursday --
in a posed photograph giving no hint of where he is hiding while
awaiting a decision on his political asylum request.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Aleman, told reporters Thursday
that Panama's decision on Montesinos will be made only in the
interest of ''contributing to a peaceful end to the Peruvian
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos, who fled Peru after a videotape showed him allegedly
bribing a Peruvian lawmaker, arrived in Panama on Sunday. The
scandal over the video prompted Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
to call early elections in which he will not be a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, published on the front page of the daily
newspaper El Panama America, showed Montesinos seated and appearing
to read a book. Beside him is a small white table holding a glass
of water and a vase of tropical flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not spontaneous; he posed,'' said the newspaper's news
editor, Octavio Amat. He said Montesinos agreed to one photograph
on condition that he choreograph the shot and that the newspaper
promise not to tell where it was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ''They allowed us to send one of our people, but only under
strict security,'' Amat said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people who accompanied Montesinos to Panama, including a
Peruvian general, were kicked out of the country on Tuesday after
government officials said they had illegally entered on tourist
visas.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos' asking for political asylum provoked a furor in
Panama, which has a history of providing refuge to deposed Latin
American strongmen.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanians who want to clean up the country's reputation oppose
granting Motesinos asylum, as do opposition Peruvian lawmakers who
want to see him prosecuted in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   President Mireya Moscoso has come under strong pressure from the
Organization of American States and regional heads of state to
accept Montesinos, especially after reports that his supporters in
Peru might stage a coup if he were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso has said that while she considers the asylum request,
Montesinos could stay in Panama under a visa granted by a previous
Panamanian president.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very hard decision to make,'' Aleman, the foreign
minister, said before leaving for a summit of Central American
leaders in Guatemala. ''It will be a hemispheric gesture that
attempts to contribute to a peaceful end to the Peruvian crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 2323 </TRAILER>
