<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Appears on CNN Talk Show  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore says all those hits he's taking about
exaggerating aspects of his past are, well, exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a campaign, you know, if you get a fact wrong, all of a
sudden you are accused of committing some horrible offense,'' he
said Thursday on CNN's ''Larry King Live,'' a touch defensive
during a mostly smooth hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate and his wife Tipper
appeared on King's show two nights after Republican George W. Bush
and his wife Laura came on to answer questions from the talk show
host and a few call-in viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pronounced himself relaxed about next Tuesday's TV debate
with his Republican opponent, the first of three coming up in their
close contest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the debate preparations he will be doing this weekend
in Sarasota, Fla., will consist of reading ''pretty boring''
briefing books, as well as practice debate sessions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The older I get, the less I'm nervous about things that might
have made me nervous when I was younger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet again Gore was asked about his motives behind the long kiss
he gave his wife while taking the stage at the Democratic National
Convention. Was he trying to send a message to voters that he is
devoted to his wife and not like President Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   ''I was trying to send a message to Tipper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like I said, message received,'' Tipper Gore said, describing
the kiss as ''pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he thinks he can win Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb
is governor but polls indicate a close race. But he admitted he
doesn't have much hope of carrying Texas, where Bush himself is
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was somewhat uncomfortable when asked about
misrepresentations he's made during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that itself is an exaggeration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore pitched in, saying that sometimes ''you're just
talking, you're just thinking ... just being yourself'' when
certain things are said and then put under a microscope. ''I just
think people have to understand all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore recently represented figures in a study as prices actually
paid for an arthritis medicine for his mother-in-law and his dog,
even though the numbers were not related to his family's
experience. He was trying to make a point about drugs costing more
for people than pets.
</P>
<P>
   And he claimed to have remembered a union song from childhood
even though it was not written until he was an adult. After that
was pointed out, he said he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   Gore picked the Mote Marine Laboratory in Sarasota -- a shark
research station -- for his debate rehearsals after considering Cape
Cod or Boston, the city where he meets Bush on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides said they were outhustled for Massachusetts
accommodations by tourists crowding in to see the changing leaves.
</P>
<P>
   But they said Sarasota is fine, given Florida's importance in
the Nov. 7 election and the fact that the area has many senior
citizens living on fixed incomes -- the sort of people who might
like Gore's plans for a Medicare drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any time we can get the vice president in a position in
Florida where he is talking about issues is a plus for us,'' said
Doug Hattaway, speaking for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will be going to Sarasota on Saturday and leaving directly
from there for Boston on Tuesday morning, Hattaway said. Gore was
planning a public event with seniors while in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 2326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000928.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Miami Manager Pleads Innocent  </HEADLINE>
By ADRIAN SAINZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The former city manager fired after the Elian
Gonzalez raid pleaded innocent Thursday to federal charges alleging
he took more than $86,000 from a police pension fund and a charity.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Warshaw, who was once Miami's assistant police chief and
had been widely credited with cleaning up corruption, is charged
with one count of conspiracy and four counts of mail fraud and
faces one to three years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is probably, with the exception the day my father died,
the saddest day of my life,'' Warshaw said after his initial
hearing. ''I probably could have used better judgment for what I
did, but that's in the past now. All I can do about it is defend
myself when I get my day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw, who also was once Miami's chief of police, was released
on $100,000 bond. His arraignment was set for Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses Warshaw of using the pension fund's
American Express card to buy $16,775 worth of hockey tickets. It
also says nearly $70,000 was taken from the charity Do the Right
Thing Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw was chairman of the pension fund from 1991 to 1998 and
secretary and treasurer of the charity from 1991 until August. The
dates in the indictment range from May 1993 to April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw has blamed his problems on sloppy record-keeping and
said the money had been repaid.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also named the charity's former accountant, who
committed suicide last year. A note found after the suicide led to
the investigation, Miami-Dade Police Chief Carlos Alvarez said.
</P>
<P>
   As city manager, Warshaw was known for his stand against
corruption and for helping restore the city's financial health
after a 1996 kickback scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Joe Carollo fired him in April, accusing him of lying and
mismanagement, after Warshaw refused to fire Police Chief William
O'Brien in the wake of the federal raid that removed 6-year-old
Elian from his Miami relatives and reunited him with his Cuban
father. O'Brien did not notify the mayor of plans for the raid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-28-00 2328 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000928.0236 </DOCNO>
